{"title_page": "Christchurch", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{redirect|Chch|the Ontario TV station|CHCH-DT|other uses of Christchurch|Christchurch (disambiguation)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox Settlement for additional fields that may be available -->\n<!-- See the Table at Infobox Settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage -->\n<!-- Basic info ---------------->\n|name = Christchurch\n|native_name = {{native name|mi|\u014ctautahi|nbsp=omit}}\n|named_for = [[Christ Church, Oxford]]\n|settlement_type = [[Cities of New Zealand|City]] <!-- e.g. Town, Village, City, etc. -->\n|image_skyline = {{multiple image\n|border                 = infobox\n|total_width            = 290\n|image_style            = border:1;\n|perrow                 = 1/2/2/2\n|image1                 = Christchurch City.jpg\n|image2                 = Christchurch Tram. No 11. (11261719684).jpg\n|image3                 = Christchurch Art Gallery. (9450846394).jpg\n|image4                 = Christchurch Adventure Park.jpg\n|image5                 = HagleyParkAerialPhoto.jpg\n|image6                 = New Regent St Christchurch. (10588849634).jpg\n|image7                 = Water fountain at Christchurch Botanical Gardens.JPG\n}}\n|image_caption = '''Clockwise from top:''' City skyline, [[Christchurch Art Gallery]], aerial view of [[Hagley Park, Christchurch|Hagley Park]], the Peacock Fountain in the [[Christchurch Botanic Gardens]], [[New Regent Street]], [[Christchurch Adventure Park]], [[Christchurch tramway system|Christchurch Trams]]\n|image_flag = Chch FLAG.jpg\n|flag_size = \n|image_seal = \n|seal_size = \n|image_shield = Chch COA.JPG\n|shield_link = Coat of arms of the City of Christchurch\n|nickname = The Garden City\n|motto = ''Fide Condita Fructu Beata Spe Fortis'' ''<br/>[[English language|English]]: ''Founded in Faith, Rich in the Fulfillment thereof, Strong in Hope for the Future''\n<!-- images and maps ----------->\n|image_map = \n|mapsize = \n|map_caption = \n|pushpin_map = New Zealand South Island#New Zealand\n|pushpin_label_position = top\n|pushpin_mapsize = \n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|pushpin_map_caption = \n|coordinates = {{coord|43|31|48|S|172|37|13|E|region:NZ|display=inline,title}}\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|subdivision_type = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name = {{NZL}}\n|subdivision_type1 = [[List of islands of New Zealand|Island]]\n|subdivision_type2 = [[Regions of New Zealand|Region]]\n|subdivision_type3 = [[Territorial authority]]\n|subdivision_type4 = Wards\n|subdivision_name1 = [[South Island]]\n|subdivision_name2 = [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]]\n|subdivision_name3 = [[Christchurch City Council]]\n|subdivision_name4 = Banks Peninsula<br>Burwood<br>Cashmere<br>Central<br>Coastal<br>Fendalton<br>Halswell<br>Harewood<br>Heathcote<br>Hornby<br>Innes<br>Linwood<br>Papanui<br>Riccarton<br>Spreydon<br>Waimairi\n<!-- etc. up to p50: for separate parts to be listed -->\n<!-- Politics ----------------->\n|established_title = Settled by the UK\n|established_date = 1848\n|established_title1 = \n|established_date1 = \n<!-- Area --------------------->\n|government_footnotes = \n|government_type = \n|leader_title = [[Mayor of Christchurch|Mayor]]\n|leader_name = [[Lianne Dalziel]]\n|total_type = Territorial <!-- to set a non-standard label for total area and population rows -->\n|unit_pref = <!-- Enter: Imperial, to display imperial before metric -->\n|area_footnotes = \n|area_magnitude = \n|area_total_km2 = 1426<!-- Region--> <!-- ALL fields with measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion -->\n|area_land_km2 = <!-- See table @ Template:Infobox Settlement for details on unit conversion -->\n|area_water_km2 = \n|area_water_percent = \n|area_urban_km2 = 607.73\n<!-- Elevation -------------------------->\n|elevation_footnotes = <ref>{{cite web |title=NZ Topographic Map |url=https://www.topomap.co.nz/ |publisher=[[Land Information New Zealand]] |accessdate=25 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927193604/http://www.topomap.co.nz/ |archive-date=27 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|elevation_m = 20\n<!-- Population ----------------------->\n|population_total = {{NZ population data 2018|Christchurch city|y}}\n|population_as_of = {{NZ population data 2018|||y}}\n|population_footnotes ={{NZ population data 2018||||y}}\n|population_density_km2 = auto\n|population_urban = {{NZ population data 2018|Christchurch|y}}\n|population_density_urban_km2 = auto\n|population_blank1_title = [[Demonym]]\n|population_blank1 = Cantabrian\n<!-- General information --------------->\n|population_note =\n|postal_code_type = Postcode(s)\n|postal_code = 8011, 8013, 8014, 8022, 8023, 8024, 8025, 8041, 8042, 8051, 8052, 8053, 8061, 8062, 8081, 8082, 8083\n|area_code = 03\n|website = [http://www.ccc.govt.nz www.ccc.govt.nz] <br/> [http://www.ecan.govt.nz www.ecan.govt.nz]\n|footnotes = \n|timezone = [[Time in New Zealand|NZST]]\n|utc_offset = +12\n|timezone_DST = NZDT\n|utc_offset_DST = +13\n|coor_type = \n|blank_name = Local [[iwi]]\n|blank_info = [[Ng\u0101i Tahu]], [[K\u0101ti M\u0101moe]]\n}}\n\n[[File:High, Manchester and Lichfield Streets in Christchurch, 8 May 1923.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|High, Manchester and Lichfield Streets in Christchurch, 1923]]\n\n'''Christchurch''' ({{IPAc-en|'|k|r|a\u026a|s|t\u0283|\u025cr|t\u0283}}; {{lang-mi|\u014ctautahi}}) is the largest city in the [[South Island]] of [[New Zealand]] and the seat of the [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury Region]]. The Christchurch urban area lies on the South Island's east coast, just north of [[Banks Peninsula]]. The urban area is home to {{NZ population data 2018|Christchurch|y}} residents,<ref name=\"NZ_population_data_2018\"/> and the territorial authority has {{NZ population data 2018|Christchurch city|y}} people,{{NZ population data 2018||||y}} which makes it the second-most<!-- see [[List of cities in New Zealand]] for details --> populous city in New Zealand after [[Auckland]] and before [[Wellington]]. The [[Avon River (Canterbury)|Avon River]] flows through the centre of the city, with an urban park located along its banks.\n\nArchaeological evidence has indicated that people first settled in the Christchurch area in about 1250. Christchurch became a city by [[Royal Charter]] on 31 July 1856, making it officially the oldest established city in New Zealand. The [[Canterbury Association]], which settled the [[Canterbury Plains]], named the city after [[Christ Church, Oxford]]. The new settlement was laid out in a [[grid pattern]] centred on [[Cathedral Square, Christchurch|Cathedral Square]]; during the 19th century there were few barriers to the rapid growth of the urban area, except for the Pacific to the east and the [[Port Hills]] to the south.\n\n[[Agriculture in New Zealand|Agriculture]] is the historic mainstay of Christchurch's economy. The early presence of the [[University of Canterbury]] and the heritage of the city's academic institutions in association with local businesses has fostered a number of technology-based industries. Christchurch is one of five 'gateway cities' for [[History of Antarctica|Antarctic exploration]], hosting Antarctic support bases for several nations.<ref>{{cite web |title=Christchurch \u2013 Gateway to Antarctica |url=http://www.antarcticanz.govt.nz/about-us/christchurch-gateway-to-antarctica/ |publisher=Antarctica New Zealand |access-date=23 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323210404/http://www.antarcticanz.govt.nz/about-us/christchurch-gateway-to-antarctica/ |archive-date=23 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe city suffered [[2011 Christchurch earthquake|a series of earthquakes]] between September 2010 and January 2012, with the most destructive of them occurring at 12.51 p.m. on Tuesday, 22 February 2011, in which 185 people were killed and thousands of buildings across the city collapsed or suffered severe damage. By late 2013, 1,500 buildings in the city had been demolished, leading to an ongoing recovery and rebuilding project.\n\n==Names==\nThe name of \"Christchurch\" was agreed on at the first meeting of the [[Canterbury Association]] on 27 March 1848. It was suggested by founder [[John Robert Godley]], whose [[alma mater]] was [[Christ Church, Oxford]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|last1=Cowie|first1=D. J.|title=How Christchurch Got Its Name \u2013 A Controverted Subject|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-Gov09_04Rail-t1-body-d14.html|publisher=Victoria University of Wellington|accessdate=15 August 2017|date=1934|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610182504/http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-Gov09_04Rail-t1-body-d14.html|archive-date=10 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[M\u0101ori language|M\u0101ori]] name ''\u014ctautahi'' (\"the place of Tautahi\") was adopted in the 1930s; originally it was the name of a specific site by the Avon River (near present-day Kilmore Street).<ref>{{cite web|title=\u014ctautahi \u2013 Christchurch|url=https://my.christchurchcitylibraries.com/ti-kouka-whenua/otautahi/|publisher=Christchurch City Libraries|accessdate=15 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161101022827/http://my.christchurchcitylibraries.com/ti-kouka-whenua/otautahi/|archive-date=1 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The site was a seasonal dwelling of [[Ng\u0101i Tahu]] chief [[Te Potiki Tautahi]], whose main home was [[Port Levy]] on Banks Peninsula. Prior to that the Ng\u0101i Tahu generally referred to the Christchurch area as ''Karaitiana'',<ref>[http://christchurchcitylibraries.com/tikoukawhenua/otautahi/ \u014ctautahi] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725065207/http://christchurchcitylibraries.com/tikoukawhenua/otautahi/ |date=25 July 2011 }} (from the Christchurch City Library website)</ref> a transliteration of the English word [[Christianity|Christian]].\n\n\"ChCh\" is sometimes used as an abbreviation of \"Christchurch\".\n\n==History==\n{{see also|History of the Canterbury Region}}\n\n===M\u0101ori settlement===\n{{unreferenced section|date=March 2019}}\nArchaeological evidence found in a cave at [[Redcliffs]] in 1876 has indicated that the Christchurch area was first settled by [[moa]]-hunting tribes about 1250 CE. These first inhabitants were thought to have been followed by the [[Waitaha (South Island iwi)|Waitaha]] iwi, who are said to have migrated from the East coast of the North Island in the 16th century. Following tribal warfare, the Waitaha (made of three peoples) were dispossessed by the [[K\u0101ti M\u0101moe|Ng\u0101ti M\u0101moe]] iwi. They were in turn subjugated by the [[Ng\u0101i Tahu]] iwi, who remained in control until the arrival of European settlers.\n\n===European settlement===\nFollowing the purchase of land at Putaringamotu (modern Riccarton) by the [[Weller brothers]], whalers of [[Otago]] and Sydney, a party of European settlers led by Herriott and McGillivray established themselves in what is now Christchurch, early in 1840. Their abandoned holdings were taken over by brothers [[William Deans|William]] and [[John Deans (pioneer)|John Deans]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.riccartonhouse.co.nz/deans_cottage/ |title=Deans cottage web site |publisher=Riccartonhouse.co.nz |accessdate=23 February 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110724194344/http://www.riccartonhouse.co.nz/deans_cottage/ |archive-date=24 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> in 1843 who stayed. The [[First Four Ships]] were chartered by the [[Canterbury Association]] and brought the first 792 of the ''Canterbury Pilgrims'' to [[Lyttelton, New Zealand|Lyttelton Harbour]]. These sailing vessels were the ''[[Randolph (ship)|Randolph]]'', ''[[Charlotte Jane]]'', {{ship||Sir George Seymour|1844 ship|2}}, and ''[[Cressy (ship)|Cressy]]''. The ''Charlotte Jane'' was the first to arrive on 16 December 1850. The Canterbury Pilgrims had aspirations of building a city around a cathedral and college, on the model of [[Christ Church, Oxford|Christ Church]] in [[Oxford]].<ref>[http://www.christchurchcathedral.co.nz/discover/cathedral_history.html Cathedral History] (from the official [[ChristChurch Cathedral]] website). {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017103748/http://christchurchcathedral.co.nz/discover/cathedral_history.html |date=17 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe name \"Christ Church\" was decided prior to the ships' arrival, at the Association's first meeting, on 27 March 1848. The exact basis for the name is not known. It has been suggested that it is named for [[Christchurch, Dorset|Christchurch]], in [[Dorset]], England; for [[Canterbury Cathedral]]; or in honour of [[Christ Church, Oxford|Christ Church]], Oxford. The last explanation is the one generally accepted.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAt the request of the Deans brothers \u2014 whose farm was the earliest European settlement in the area \u2013 the river was named after the [[River Avon, Falkirk|River Avon]] in Scotland, which rises in the [[Ayrshire]] hills near to where their grandfather's farm was located.<ref name=\"HIGHT\">''A History of Canterbury'', Vol. 1 \u2013 Sir James Hight & Straubel, C.R.; Canterbury Centennial Association and Whitcombe and Tombs, Christchurch 1957, Page 121</ref>\n\nCaptain [[Joseph Thomas (surveyor)|Joseph Thomas]], the Canterbury Association's Chief Surveyor, surveyed the surrounding area. By December 1849 he had commissioned the construction of a road from Port Cooper, later [[Lyttelton, New Zealand|Lyttelton]], to Christchurch via [[Sumner, New Zealand|Sumner]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://library.christchurch.org.nz/Heritage/EarlyChristchurch/JosephThomas.asp |title=Captain Thomas and the Streets of Christchurch|publisher=[[Christchurch City Libraries]]|access-date=14 May 2008|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080829232049/http://library.christchurch.org.nz/Heritage/EarlyChristchurch/JosephThomas.asp |archive-date=29 August 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref> However, this proved more difficult than expected and road construction was stopped while a steep foot and [[Packhorse|pack horse]] track was constructed over the hill between the port and the Heathcote valley, where access to the site of the proposed settlement could be gained. This track became known as the [[Bridle Path (New Zealand)|Bridle Path]], because the path was so steep that pack horses needed to be led by the bridle.<ref>''Rescue, the Sumner community and its lifeboat service'' \u2013 Amodeo, Colin (editor), Christchurch: Sumner Lifeboat Institution Incorporated, 1998</ref>\n\nGoods that were too heavy or bulky to be transported by pack horse over the Bridle Path were shipped by small sailing vessels some eight miles (13&nbsp;km) by water around the coast and up the [[Avon Heathcote Estuary]] to [[Ferrymead]]. New Zealand's first public railway line, the [[Ferrymead Railway]], opened from Ferrymead to Christchurch in 1863. Due to the difficulties in travelling over the [[Port Hills]] and the dangers associated with shipping navigating the Sumner bar, a [[Lyttelton Rail Tunnel|railway tunnel]] was built through the Port Hills to Lyttelton, opening in 1867.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://my.christchurchcitylibraries.com/lyttelton-road-tunnel/ |title=Chch City Libraries |publisher=my.christchurchcitylibraries.com |date=26 January 2010 |accessdate=5 March 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150402134130/http://my.christchurchcitylibraries.com/lyttelton-road-tunnel/ |archive-date=2 April 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:ChristChurch Cathedral, 1880s.jpg|thumb|[[ChristChurch Cathedral]] (pictured in the {{circa|1880s}}) was constructed between 1864 and 1904.]]\nChristchurch became a city by [[royal charter]] on 31 July 1856, the first in New Zealand. Many of the city's [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival]] buildings by architect [[Benjamin Mountfort]] date from this period. Christchurch was the seat of provincial administration for the [[Canterbury Province|Province of Canterbury]], which was abolished in 1876. Christchurch buildings were damaged by earthquakes in [[1869 Christchurch earthquake|1869]], [[1881 Castle Hill earthquake |1881]] and [[1888 North Canterbury earthquake|1888]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://my.christchurchcitylibraries.com/christchurch-and-canterbury-earthquakes/|title=Christchurch and Canterbury earthquakes|website=my.christchurchcitylibraries.com|language=en-NZ|access-date=23 December 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181223121335/https://my.christchurchcitylibraries.com/christchurch-and-canterbury-earthquakes/ |archive-date=23 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===1900\u20132000===\n[[File:Aerial_photograph_of_Christchurch,_1918.jpg|thumb|First ever aerial photograph of Christchurch taken by [[Leslie Hinge]], 1918]]\nIn 1947, New Zealand's worst fire disaster occurred at [[Ballantyne's fire|Ballantyne's Department Store]] in the inner city, with 41 people killed in a blaze which razed the rambling collection of buildings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://my.christchurchcitylibraries.com/ballantynes-fire/ |title=Ballantyne's fire |publisher=my.christchurchcitylibraries.com |date=18 November 1947 |accessdate=5 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150319214357/http://my.christchurchcitylibraries.com/ballantynes-fire/ |archive-date=19 March 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Lyttelton road tunnel]] between Lyttelton and Christchurch was opened in 1964.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/Places/Canterbury/CanterburyPlaces/10/ENZ-Resources/Standard/4/en |title=Te Ara |publisher=Te Ara |date=2 March 2009 |accessdate=23 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090330104118/http://www.teara.govt.nz/Places/Canterbury/CanterburyPlaces/10/ENZ-Resources/Standard/4/en |archive-date=30 March 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nChristchurch hosted the [[1974 British Commonwealth Games]].\n\n===Modern history===\n\n====2010\u20132012 earthquakes====\n{{Main|2010 Canterbury earthquake|February 2011 Christchurch earthquake|June 2011 Christchurch earthquake}}\n[[File:Pyne Gould Building destroyed by earthquake, Christchurch, New Zealand - 20110224.jpg|thumb|right|The collapsed Pyne Gould Building. Thirty of the building's two hundred workers were trapped within the building following the February 2011 earthquake.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10708101|title=Christchurch Earthquake: Workers trapped in crushed buildings|work=New Zealand Herald|date=22 February 2011|access-date=21 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120124032934/http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10708101|archive-date=24 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>]]\nOn Saturday 4 September 2010, [[2010 Canterbury earthquake|a magnitude 7.1 earthquake]] struck Christchurch and the central Canterbury region at 4:35&nbsp;am. Located near [[Darfield, New Zealand|Darfield]], west of the city at a depth of {{convert|10|km|mi}}, it caused widespread damage to the city and minor injuries, but no direct fatalities.<ref>{{citation |url= http://www.radionz.co.nz/news/national/55956/strong-quake-hits-near-christchurch |title=Strong quake hits in Darfield, Canterbury near Christchurch |publisher=Radio New Zealand |date=4 September 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"bloomberg\">{{cite web|title=New Zealand's South Island Rocked by Magnitude 7.0 Earthquake|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-04/new-zealand-s-christchurch-rocked-by-7-0-earthquake-declares-emergency.html|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|accessdate=4 September 2010|date=3 September 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100906214008/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-04/new-zealand-s-christchurch-rocked-by-7-0-earthquake-declares-emergency.html|archive-date=6 September 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNearly six months later on Tuesday 22 February 2011, [[February 2011 Christchurch earthquake|a second earthquake]] measuring magnitude 6.3 struck the city at 12:51&nbsp;pm. It was located closer to the city, near Lyttelton at a depth of {{convert|5|km|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"GeoNet6.3\">{{cite web\n |title=New Zealand Earthquake Report \u2013 Feb&nbsp;22, 2011 at 12:51&nbsp;pm (NZDT)\n |work=[[GeoNet]]\n |publisher=[[Earthquake Commission]] and [[GNS Science]]\n |url=http://www.geonet.org.nz/earthquake/quakes/3468575g.html\n |date=22 February 2011\n |accessdate=22 February 2011\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110223092531/http://www.geonet.org.nz/earthquake/quakes/3468575g.html\n |archivedate=23 February 2011\n }}</ref>\nAlthough lower on the [[moment magnitude scale]] than the previous earthquake, the intensity and violence of the ground shaking was measured to be [[Mercalli intensity scale|IX (''Violent'')]], among the strongest ever recorded globally in an urban area<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/4714748/Building-code-no-match-for-earthquake\n|title=Building code no match for earthquake\n|first=Andrea\n|last=Fox\n|work=The Dominion Post\n|date=1 March 2011\n|accessdate=11 July 2011\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108021901/http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/4714748/Building-code-no-match-for-earthquake\n|archive-date=8 January 2012\n|url-status=live\n}}</ref> and in total 185 people were killed.<ref name=now184>{{cite web |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/6394084/February-earthquake-toll-hits-185 |title= Official quake toll rises to 185 |date= 9 February 2012 |publisher= Stuff.co |accessdate= 9 February 2012 |archive-url= https://www.webcitation.org/6AuTMs7VB?url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/6394084/February-earthquake-toll-hits-185 |archive-date= 24 September 2012 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref name=\"listdeceased\">{{cite web |url= http://www.police.govt.nz/list-deceased |title= List of deceased \u2013 Christchurch earthquake |publisher= New Zealand Police |date= 8 September 2011 |accessdate= 26 December 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110614023925/http://www.police.govt.nz/list-deceased |archive-date= 14 June 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> People from more than 20 countries were among the victims.<ref name=\"NZH-toll\">{{cite news|title=Earthquake toll rises to 145|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10708888|accessdate=26 February 2011|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|date=26 February 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117082028/http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10708888|archive-date=17 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The city's iconic [[ChristChurch Cathedral, Christchurch|ChristChurch Cathedral]]<!--The unusual spelling 'ChristChurch' here is correct - See the note on the discussion page--> was severely damaged and lost its spire.<ref name=\"DomPost\">{{cite web |title=Large quake strikes Christchurch |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/4688231/Large-quake-strikes-Christchurch |work=Dominion Post |accessdate=22 February 2011 |year=2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AuTPnpjj?url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/4688231/Large-quake-strikes-Christchurch |archivedate=24 September 2012  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10708016 |title=Christchurch quake: People likely to be trapped in cathedral |newspaper=New Zealand Herald |date=22 February 2011 |accessdate=22 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111116021950/http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10708016 |archive-date=16 November 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The collapse of the [[CTV Building]] resulted in the majority of fatalities. Widespread damage across Christchurch resulted in loss of homes, major buildings and infrastructure. Significant [[soil liquefaction|liquefaction]] affected the eastern suburbs, and the total cost to insurers of rebuilding has been estimated at NZ$20\u201330&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"eatGDP\">{{cite web |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/rebuilding-christchurch/4984173/Quake-rebuild-will-eat-into-GDP |first= Fiona |last= Rotherham |date= 10 May 2011 |accessdate= 15 May 2011 |title= Quake rebuild will eat into GDP |publisher= Stuff.co.nz |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110513072810/http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/rebuilding-christchurch/4984173/Quake-rebuild-will-eat-into-GDP |archive-date= 13 May 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref name=\"jpmorgan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-22/new-zealand-s-earthquake-may-become-costliest-insured-disaster-since-2008.html|title=New Zealand's Earthquake May Become Costliest Insured Disaster Since 2008|first1=Noah|last1=Buhayar|first2=Jacob|last2=Greber|first3=Nichola|last3=Saminather|work=Bloomberg L.P.|date=23 February 2011|accessdate=24 February 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110225003215/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-22/new-zealand-s-earthquake-may-become-costliest-insured-disaster-since-2008.html|archive-date=25 February 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThere were continuing aftershocks for some time, with 4,558 above a magnitude 3.0 recorded in the Canterbury region from 4 September 2010 to 3 September 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://info.geonet.org.nz/display/home/Canterbury+Aftershocks |title=Canterbury Aftershocks |publisher=Info.geonet.org.nz |accessdate=11 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109074032/http://info.geonet.org.nz/display/home/Canterbury+Aftershocks |archive-date=9 January 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Particularly large events on 13 June 2011,<ref name=\"Stuff.co.nz_5139229\">{{cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/christchurch-earthquake-2011/5139229/Thousands-of-homes-need-to-go |title=Thousands of homes need to go |date=14 June 2011 |work=[[The Press]] |accessdate=24 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110902085417/http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/christchurch-earthquake-2011/5139229/Thousands-of-homes-need-to-go |archive-date=2 September 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> 23 December 2011,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-16312041 |title=New Zealand's Christchurch rocked by earthquakes |publisher=BBC |date=23 December 2011 |accessdate=4 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131127111230/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-16312041 |archive-date=27 November 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10775100 |title=Christchurch: More quakes expected |publisher=nzherald.co.nz |date=23 December 2011 |accessdate=4 November 2013 |newspaper=NZ Herald |last1=Herald |first1=Apnz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105010107/http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10775100 |archive-date=5 November 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Readiness Is All |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/evacuations-large-quake-rocks-christchurch-4667810 |title=Evacuations as large quake rocks Christchurch |publisher=TVNZ |date=23 December 2011 |accessdate=4 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119230006/http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/evacuations-large-quake-rocks-christchurch-4667810 |archive-date=19 January 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> and 2 January 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/6207076/Quake-swarm-rattles-Christchurch|title=Quake swarm rattles Christchurch|work=Stuff|access-date=2 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120103192101/http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/6207076/Quake-swarm-rattles-Christchurch|archive-date=3 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> all caused further damage and minor injuries; but no further deaths.\n\nFollowing the earthquakes over 1500 buildings in the city had been demolished or partly demolished by September 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/content/tvnz/onenews/story/2013/09/09/christchurch-demolition-phase-draws-to-an-end.html |title=Christchurch demolition phase draws to an end |work=One News |date=9 September 2013 |accessdate=12 June 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919212141/https://www.tvnz.co.nz/content/tvnz/onenews/story/2013/09/09/christchurch-demolition-phase-draws-to-an-end.html |archive-date=19 September 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Christchurch cherry blossoms and water wheel.jpg|thumb|Cherry blossom trees in Spring bloom and a historic water wheel, located on a small island in the [[Avon River (Canterbury)|Avon River]] at the corner of Oxford Terrace and Hereford Street, [[Hagley Park (New Zealand)|Hagley Park]] in the city centre.]]\n\nThe city experienced rapid growth following the earthquakes. A Christchurch Central Recovery Plan guides rebuilding in the central city. There has been massive growth in the residential sector, with around 50,000 new houses expected to be constructed in the Greater Christchurch area by 2028 as outlined in the Land Use Recovery Plan (LURP).\n\n====2013 to 2018====\nOn 13 February 2017, [[2017 Port Hills fires|two bush fires started]] on the [[Port Hills]]. These merged over the next two days and the single very large wild fire extended down both sides of the Port Hill almost reaching [[Governors Bay]] in the south-west, and the [[Westmorland, New Zealand|Westmorland]], [[Kennedys Bush]], and Dyers Pass Road almost down to the [[Sign of the Takahe]]. Eleven houses were destroyed by fire, over one thousand residents were evacuated from their homes, and over {{convert|2076|ha}} of land was burned.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/89489080/how-does-the-size-of-the-christchurch-fires-compare |work=[[stuff.co.nz]] |date=17 February 2017 |access-date=17 February 2017 |title=How does the size of the Christchurch fires compare? |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170309085645/http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/89489080/how-does-the-size-of-the-christchurch-fires-compare |archive-date=9 March 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== 2019 terrorist attacks ====\n{{Main|Christchurch mosque shootings}}\n[[File:Christchurch Mosque, New Zealand.jpg|thumb|Masjid (mosque) Al Noor]]\nFifty-one people died from two consecutive terrorist attacks at [[Al Noor Mosque, Christchurch|Al Noor Mosque]] and [[Linwood Islamic Centre]] by an [[Australia]]n [[white supremacist]] carried out on 15 March 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Police with the latest information on the mosque shootings |url=https://www.radionz.co.nz/news/national/384896/police-with-the-latest-information-on-the-mosque-shootings |accessdate=17 March 2019 | work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=17 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Turkish man wounded in Christchurch mosque shootings has died, bringing toll to 51 |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/christchurch-shooting/112429722/turkish-man-wounded-in-christchurch-attacks-dies |accessdate=3 May 2019 |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |date=3 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190503000711/https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/christchurch-shooting/112429722/turkish-man-wounded-in-christchurch-attacks-dies |archive-date=3 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Christchurch mosque shooting: What you need to know |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12213056 |accessdate=15 March 2019 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=15 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190315025815/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12213056 |archive-date=15 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Christchurch shooting: reports of multiple casualties after shooting at mosque \u2013 live updates |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2019/mar/15/christchurch-shooting-injuries-reported-as-police-respond-to-critical-incident-live |accessdate=15 March 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=15 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190315024555/https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2019/mar/15/christchurch-shooting-injuries-reported-as-police-respond-to-critical-incident-live |archive-date=15 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Molyneux |first1=Vita |title=Live updates: Six people have reportedly been killed in Christchurch shootings near mosque |url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2019/03/gunshots-heard-near-hagley-park-in-christchurch.html |accessdate=15 March 2019 |publisher=[[Newshub]] |date=15 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190315031109/https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/new-zealand/2019/03/gunshots-heard-near-hagley-park-in-christchurch.html |archive-date=15 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The terrorist attacks have been described by [[Prime Minister of New Zealand|Prime Minister]] [[Jacinda Ardern]] as \"One of New Zealand's darkest days\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/mar/15/one-of-new-zealands-darkest-days-jacinda-ardern-responds-to-christchurch-shooting|title=Jacinda Ardern on the Christchurch shooting: 'One of New Zealand's darkest days|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=5 July 2019|date=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Christchurch, New Zealand, NASA 2.jpg|thumb|right|Satellite image showing Christchurch and surrounding areas.]]\n[[File:STS-116 spacewalk 1.jpg|thumb|View of the Christchurch region from the [[International Space Station]].]]\nChristchurch lies in [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]], near the centre of the east coast of the [[South Island]], east of the [[Canterbury Plains]]. It is located near the southern end of [[Pegasus Bay]], and is bounded to the east by the Pacific Ocean coast and the [[Avon Heathcote Estuary|estuary]] of the [[Avon River (Canterbury)|Avon]] and [[Heathcote River]]s. To the south and south-east the urban portion of the city is limited by the volcanic slopes of the [[Port Hills]] separating it from Banks Peninsula. To the north the city is bounded by the braided [[Waimakariri River]].\n\nChristchurch is one of a group of only four current cities in the world to have been carefully planned following the same layout of a central city square, four complementing city squares surrounding it and a parklands area that embrace the city centre. The first city built with this pattern was [[Philadelphia]]. Later came [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]] and [[Adelaide]], before Christchurch.<ref>{{cite book|title=Adelaide|first=Kerryn|last=Goldsworthy|year=2011|publisher=NewSouth|isbn=9-7817-4224092-3|pp=83}}</ref>\n\nChristchurch has one of the highest-quality [[water supply|water supplies]] in the world, with its water rated among the purest and cleanest in the world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ccc.govt.nz/LTCCP/CommunityOutcomes/BaselineReport/Environment/ |title=Community Outcomes Baseline Report |publisher=Christchurch City Council |date=4 September 2010 |accessdate=23 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081016154738/http://www.ccc.govt.nz/LTCCP/CommunityOutcomes/BaselineReport/Environment/ |archive-date=16 October 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> Untreated, naturally filtered water is sourced, via more than 50 pumping stations surrounding the city, from [[aquifer]]s emanating from the foothills of the [[Southern Alps (New Zealand)|Southern Alps]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ccc.govt.nz/homeliving/watersupply/ourwater/whereourwatercomesfrom.aspx |title=Where our water comes from |publisher=Christchurch City Council |date=4 September 2010 |accessdate=23 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120618111101/http://www.ccc.govt.nz/homeliving/watersupply/ourwater/whereourwatercomesfrom.aspx |archive-date=18 June 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Central City===\n{{Main|Christchurch Central City}}\n[[File:View looking west-south-west from the Cathedral Tower, Christchurch.jpg|thumb|left|Worcester Street and [[Cathedral Square, Christchurch|Cathedral Square]] from the Cathedral]]\n[[File:July Snow in Christchurch, NZ.jpg|thumb|left|July snowfall on [[Cobham Intermediate School]] grounds]]\nAt the city's centre is [[Cathedral Square, Christchurch|Cathedral Square]], surrounding the now-earthquake-damaged \u2013 landmark [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] cathedral, [[ChristChurch Cathedral, Christchurch|Christ Church]]. The area around this square and within the Four Avenues of Christchurch (Bealey Avenue, Fitzgerald Avenue, Moorhouse Avenue and Deans Avenue<ref>{{cite web |url=http://resources.ccc.govt.nz/files/ResidentialDevelopment-OccupiedDwellings-docs.pdf |title=Christchurch City Council definition |accessdate=4 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130901090511/http://resources.ccc.govt.nz/files/ResidentialDevelopment-OccupiedDwellings-docs.pdf |archivedate=1 September 2013  }}</ref>) is considered to be the central business district (CBD) of the city. The central city also has a number of residential areas, including Inner City East, Inner City West, Avon Loop, Moa Neighbourhood and Victoria, but many of the residential buildings in the CBD were demolished following the February 2011 earthquakes. Cathedral Square is located at the crossing of two major central streets, [[Colombo Street]] and Worcester Street.\n\nCathedral Square, the heart of the city, hosted attractions such as (until the February 2011 earthquake)<ref name=\"Stuff.co.nz_4699902\">{{cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/marlborough-express/news/4699902/Damaged-city-too-much-for-Wizard |title=Damaged city too much for Wizard |author=Ensor, Blair |date=24 February 2011 |work=[[The Marlborough Express]] |accessdate=24 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111010132011/http://www.stuff.co.nz/marlborough-express/news/4699902/Damaged-city-too-much-for-Wizard |archive-date=10 October 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> the [[Wizard of New Zealand]], Ian Brackenbury Channell, and evangelist [[Ray Comfort]]; regular market days; free standing food and coffee carts; an aquarium, pubs and restaurants and the city's chief tourist information centre. it is expected that activities in Cathedral Square will increase as the rebuild progresses. The Wizard of New Zealand now operates from [[New Regent Street]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wizard.gen.nz/|title=Introduction to the Wizard's World|website=The Wizard of Christchurch|accessdate=12 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150729140441/http://wizard.gen.nz/|archive-date=29 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe central city also includes the pedestrianised sections of Cashel and High streets commonly known pre-earthquakes as 'City Mall'. Refurbished in 2008/09 the mall featured especially designed seating, flower and garden boxes, more trees, paving, and an extension to the central city tram route. The tram route extension was nearly complete when the February 2011 earthquake struck. Following the earthquakes, most buildings in Cashel Mall were demolished. A shopping area called [[Re:START]] opened on Cashel Street adjacent to Ballantyne's Department Store in October 2011. The Re:START mall was made of colourful shipping containers that were converted to house retail stores. The [[Bridge of Remembrance]] commemorating war dead stands at the western end of the mall, was repaired rededicated on Anzac Day, Monday 25 April 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://my.christchurchcitylibraries.com/bridge-of-remembrance/ |title=The Bridge of Remembrance Christchurch city libraries |accessdate=6 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906135554/https://my.christchurchcitylibraries.com/bridge-of-remembrance/ |archive-date=6 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ccc.govt.nz/cityleisure/artsculture/artinthecity/statues/thebridgeofremembrance.aspx |title=The Bridge of Remembrance |work=ccc.govt.nz |accessdate=31 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204174406/http://www.ccc.govt.nz/cityleisure/artsculture/artinthecity/statues/thebridgeofremembrance.aspx |archivedate=4 February 2015  }}</ref>\n\nThe Cultural Precinct<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culturalprecinct.co.nz/?PHPSESSID=cafbc554c3c9fa9d0b810570ad8e6046 |title=Welcome to Christchurch's Cultural Precinct |publisher=The Cultural Precinct of Christchurch |accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref> provided a backdrop to a vibrant scene of ever-changing arts, cultural, and heritage attractions within an area of less than one square kilometre. The [[Christchurch Arts Centre|Arts Centre]], the [[Canterbury Museum, Christchurch|Canterbury Museum]] and the [[Christchurch Art Gallery|Art Gallery]] are located in the Cultural Precinct. The majority of the activities were free and a printable map was provided. There areas are slowly being reopened follow earthquake repair and strengthening work.\n\nIn 2010, the Christchurch City Council released \"A City For People Action Plan\", a programme of work through to 2022 to improve public spaces within the central city to entice more inner city residents and visitors. A primary action was to reduce the impact of motorised private vehicles and increase the comfort of pedestrians and cyclists. The plan was based on a report prepared for the council by renowned Danish design firm [[Gehl Architects]]. Since the February [[2011 Christchurch earthquake]] Wellington architect [[Ian Athfield]] has been selected to re-plan, although many varied suggestions have been promoted for rebuilding the central city.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rebuildchristchurch.co.nz/architects-begin-to-look-at-rebuild-of-christchurch |date=1 March 2011 |title=Architects begin to look at rebuild of Christchurch |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110303142238/http://rebuildchristchurch.co.nz/architects-begin-to-look-at-rebuild-of-christchurch |archivedate=3 March 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liturgy.co.nz/blog/rebuilding-christchurch/5323 |title=Rebuilding Christchurch |accessdate=26 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110327060709/http://www.liturgy.co.nz/blog/rebuilding-christchurch/5323 |archive-date=27 March 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://nzwood.co.nz/industry-news/2010/09/21/rebuilding-christchurch-with-wood-is-a-%E2%80%98new-zealand-solution%E2%80%99/ |title=Rebuilding Christchurch with wood is a 'New Zealand solution' |access-date=26 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613113728/http://nzwood.co.nz/industry-news/2010/09/21/rebuilding-christchurch-with-wood-is-a-%e2%80%98new-zealand-solution%e2%80%99/ |archive-date=13 June 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elevatedgardencity.com/ |title=Elevated Garden City rebuilding our beloved Christchurch for the 21st century |access-date=26 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110323110729/http://www.elevatedgardencity.com/ |archive-date=23 March 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe Central City, which was fully closed off following 22 February earthquake, opened in stages and was fully reopened in June 2013. There are still some streets closed off due to earthquake damage, infrastructure repair work, and damaged buildings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10893922|title=Christchurch red zone cordon finally lifted|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|date=30 June 2013|accessdate=31 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204180125/http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10893922|archive-date=4 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Inner suburbs===\n(clockwise, starting north of the city centre)\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n*[[Mairehau]]\n*[[Shirley, New Zealand|Shirley]]\n*[[Dallington, New Zealand|Dallington]]\n*[[Richmond, Canterbury|Richmond]]\n*[[Avonside]]\n*[[Linwood, New Zealand|Linwood]]\n*[[Phillipstown, New Zealand|Phillipstown]]\n*[[Woolston, New Zealand|Woolston]]\n*[[Opawa]]\n*[[Waltham, New Zealand|Waltham]]\n*[[St Martins, New Zealand|St Martins]]\n*[[Beckenham, New Zealand|Beckenham]]\n*[[Sydenham, New Zealand|Sydenham]]\n*[[Somerfield, New Zealand|Somerfield]]\n*[[Spreydon]]\n*[[Addington, New Zealand|Addington]]\n*[[Riccarton, New Zealand|Riccarton]]\n*[[Ilam, New Zealand|Ilam]]\n*[[Upper Riccarton]]\n*[[Burnside, Canterbury|Burnside]]\n*[[Fendalton]]\n*[[Bryndwr]]\n*[[Strowan]]\n*[[Merivale]]\n*[[Papanui]]\n*[[St Albans, New Zealand|St Albans]]\n*[[Edgeware]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Outer suburbs===\n(clockwise, starting north of the city centre)\n\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n*[[Marshland, New Zealand|Marshland]]\n*[[Bottle Lake, New Zealand|Bottle Lake]]\n*[[Burwood, New Zealand|Burwood]]\n*[[Parklands, New Zealand|Parklands]]\n*[[Prestons, New Zealand|Prestons]]\n*[[Highfield, New Zealand|Highfield]]\n*[[Waimairi Beach]]\n*[[Avondale, Christchurch|Avondale]]\n*[[North New Brighton, New Zealand|North New Brighton]]\n*[[New Brighton, New Zealand|New Brighton]]\n*[[Bexley, New Zealand|Bexley]] (now largely defunct)\n*[[Aranui]]\n*[[Wainoni, Christchurch|Wainoni]]\n*[[South Brighton, Christchurch|South Brighton]]\n*[[Southshore, New Zealand|Southshore]]\n*[[Bromley, New Zealand|Bromley]]\n*[[Mount Pleasant, New Zealand|Mt Pleasant]]\n*[[Redcliffs]]\n*[[Moncks Bay]]\n*[[Clifton, Christchurch|Clifton]]\n*[[Richmond Hill, New Zealand|Richmond Hill]]\n*[[Sumner, New Zealand|Sumner]]\n*[[Scarborough, New Zealand|Scarborough Hill]]\n*[[Ferrymead]]\n*[[Heathcote Valley]]\n*[[Hillsborough, Christchurch|Hillsborough]]\n*[[Murray Aynsley Hill]]\n*[[Huntsbury]]\n*[[Cashmere, New Zealand|Cashmere]]\n*[[Westmorland, New Zealand|Westmorland]]\n*[[Hoon Hay]]\n*[[Hillmorton, New Zealand|Hillmorton]]\n*[[Aidanfield]]\n*[[Halswell]]\n*[[Kennedys Bush, New Zealand|Kennedys Bush]]\n*[[Oaklands, New Zealand|Oaklands]]\n*[[Westlake, Canterbury|Westlake]]\n*[[Longhurst, Canterbury|Longhurst]]\n*[[Knight Stream Park]]\n*[[Wigram]]\n*[[Middleton, New Zealand|Middleton]]\n*[[Sockburn, New Zealand|Sockburn]]\n*[[Hornby, New Zealand|Hornby]]\n*[[Hei Hei]]\n*[[Broomfield, New Zealand|Broomfield]]\n*[[Islington, New Zealand|Islington]]\n*[[Yaldhurst]]\n*[[Russley]]\n*[[Avonhead]]\n*[[Harewood, New Zealand|Harewood]]\n*[[Bishopdale, Christchurch|Bishopdale]]\n*[[Northcote, Christchurch|Northcote]]\n*[[Casebrook]]\n*[[Redwood, Christchurch|Redwood]]\n*[[Regents Park, Christchurch|Regents Park]]\n*[[Styx Mill]]\n*[[Northwood, New Zealand|Northwood]]\n*[[Groynes Park, New Zealand|Groynes Park]]\n*[[Belfast, New Zealand|Belfast]]\n*[[Spencerville, New Zealand|Spencerville]]\n*[[Brooklands, Christchurch|Brooklands]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Satellite towns===\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n*[[Leeston]]\n*[[Lyttelton, New Zealand|Lyttelton]]\n*[[Governors Bay]]\n*[[Diamond Harbour, New Zealand|Diamond Harbour]]\n*[[Tai Tapu]]\n*[[Little River, New Zealand|Little River]]\n*[[Lincoln, New Zealand|Lincoln]]\n*[[Prebbleton]]\n*[[Rolleston, New Zealand|Rolleston]]\n*[[Templeton, New Zealand|Templeton]]\n*[[West Melton, New Zealand|West Melton]]\n*[[Rangiora]]\n*[[Woodend, New Zealand|Woodend]]\n*[[Waikuku]]\n*[[Pegasus Town]]\n*[[Kaiapoi]]\n*[[Kainga]]\n*[[Pines Beach, New Zealand|Pines Beach]]\n*[[Akaroa]]\n*[[Motukarara]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Climate===\n{{climate chart\n|Christchurch\n|11.8|22.4|43.5\n|11.6|21.9|43.5\n|9.9|20.0|52.8\n|6.8|17.3|52.9\n|3.8|14.2|63.0\n|1.1|11.4|58.5\n|0.7|10.7|62.5\n|2.0|12.2|57.6\n|4.0|14.6|42.4\n|6.1|16.9|48.3\n|8.1|19.0|47.5\n|10.6|20.9|50.4\n|float=right\n|clear=none\n|units=metric}}\nChristchurch has a [[temperate]] [[oceanic climate]] with a mild summer, cool winter, and regular moderate rainfall. It has mean daily maximum air temperatures of {{convert|22.5|\u00b0C|0}} in January and {{convert|11.3|\u00b0C|0}} in July.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.niwa.co.nz/edu/resources/climate/maxairtemp|title=Mean Daily Maximum Temperatures 1971\u20132000|publisher=National Institute of Water and Atmospheric Research|accessdate=25 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081225155739/http://www.niwa.co.nz/edu/resources/climate/maxairtemp|archivedate=25 December 2008}}</ref> Under the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]], Christchurch has an [[oceanic climate]] (''Cfb''). Summer in the city is mostly warm but is often moderated by a [[sea breeze]] from the Northeast. A record temperature of {{convert|41.6|\u00b0C|0}} was reached in February 1973. A notable feature of the weather is the ''[[Nor'west arch|nor'wester]]'', a hot [[Foehn wind|f\u00f6hn wind]] that occasionally reaches storm force, causing widespread minor damage to property.<ref>[http://www.metservice.co.nz/default/index.php?pkey=190512&ckey=192956 Canterbury's damaging nor'wester] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050111231254/http://www.metservice.co.nz/default/index.php?pkey=190512&ckey=192956 |date=11 January 2005 }} (from the [[Meteorological Service of New Zealand Limited|Metservice NZ]] website)</ref> Like many cities, Christchurch experiences an [[urban heat island]] effect; temperatures are slightly higher within the inner city regions compared to the surrounding countryside.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Tapper|last2=Tyson|last3=Owens|last4=Hastie |first1=NJ|first2=PD|first3=IF|first4=WJ |year=1981 |title= Modeling the Winter Urban Heat Island Over Christchurch, New Zealand|journal= Journal of Applied Meteorology|volume=20|issue=4|page=289 |doi=10.1175/1520-0450(1981)020<0365:VKECOH>2.0.CO;2|issn=1520-0450|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nIn winter it is common for the temperature to fall below {{convert|0|\u00b0C}} at night. There are on average 80 days of ground frost per year.<ref>[https://www.niwa.co.nz/education-and-training/schools/resources/climate/groundfrost Mean Number Of Days Of Ground Frost] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314035433/http://www.niwa.co.nz/education-and-training/schools/resources/climate/groundfrost |date=14 March 2016 }} (from the [[National Institute of Water and Atmospheric Research|NIWA]] website)</ref> [[Snowfall]]s occur on average three times per year, although in some years no snowfall is recorded.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |url=http://docs.niwa.co.nz/library/public/nzmsmp167-2.pdf |title=The Climate of Christchurch |publisher=New Zealand Meteorological Service |accessdate=6 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140113035014/http://docs.niwa.co.nz/library/public/nzmsmp167-2.pdf |archive-date=13 January 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> The coldest temperature recorded was {{convert|-7.1|\u00b0C|0}} on 18 July 1945, the third lowest recorded temperature of New Zealand's major cities.<ref name=autogenerated1/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.niwa.co.nz/sites/default/files/import/attachments/summary.xls|title=Summary climate information for selected New Zealand location|access-date=17 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130727065226/http://www.niwa.co.nz/sites/default/files/import/attachments/summary.xls|archive-date=27 July 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn cold winter nights, the surrounding hills, clear skies, and [[frost]]y calm conditions often combine to form a stable [[Inversion (meteorology)|inversion layer]] above the city that traps vehicle exhausts and smoke from domestic fires to cause smog.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Robinson |first1=Shelley |title=Dirt, arsenic and lead polluting air in industrial Christchurch |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/business/industries/67687534/dirt-arsenic-and-lead-polluting-air-in-industrial-christchurch |accessdate=7 December 2019 |agency=Stuff |date=21 April 2015}}</ref> While not as bad as smog in Los Angeles or [[Mexico City]], Christchurch smog has often exceeded [[World Health Organization|World Health Organisation]] recommendations for air pollution. To limit air pollution, the regional council banned the use of [[fire|open fires]] in the city in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radionz.co.nz/news/regional/53393/open-fires,-old-woodburners-banned-in-christchurch|title=Open fires, old woodburners banned in Christchurch|date=1 April 2010|accessdate=31 January 2015|work=Radio New Zealdn|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403133304/http://www.radionz.co.nz/news/regional/53393/open-fires,-old-woodburners-banned-in-christchurch|archive-date=3 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2008 council prohibited the use of woodburners more than 15 years old, while making funding available to upgrade domestic home heating systems.\n{{Weather box\n|location = [[Christchurch Airport]] (1943\u20132015, Sunshine 1949\u20132015, Temperature 1953\u20132015, Humidity 1960\u20132015)\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|Jan record high C = 35.9\n|Feb record high C = 41.6\n|Mar record high C = 35.9\n|Apr record high C = 29.9\n|May record high C = 27.3\n|Jun record high C = 22.5\n|Jul record high C = 22.4\n|Aug record high C = 22.8\n|Sep record high C = 26.2\n|Oct record high C = 30.1\n|Nov record high C = 32.0\n|Dec record high C = 36.0\n|year record high C = 41.6\n|Jan high C = 22.4\n|Feb high C = 21.9\n|Mar high C = 20.0\n|Apr high C = 17.3\n|May high C = 14.2\n|Jun high C = 11.4\n|Jul high C = 10.7\n|Aug high C = 12.2\n|Sep high C = 14.6\n|Oct high C = 16.9\n|Nov high C = 19.0\n|Dec high C = 20.9\n|year high C = 16.8\n|Jan mean C = 17.1\n|Feb mean C = 16.8\n|Mar mean C = 15.0\n|Apr mean C = 12.1\n|May mean C = 9.0\n|Jun mean C = 6.2\n|Jul mean C = 5.7\n|Aug mean C = 7.1\n|Sep mean C = 9.3\n|Oct mean C = 11.5\n|Nov mean C = 13.6\n|Dec mean C = 15.7\n|year mean C = 11.6\n|Jan low C = 11.8\n|Feb low C = 11.6\n|Mar low C = 9.9\n|Apr low C = 6.8\n|May low C = 3.8\n|Jun low C = 1.1\n|Jul low C = 0.7\n|Aug low C = 2.0\n|Sep low C = 4.0\n|Oct low C = 6.1\n|Nov low C = 8.1\n|D