{"title_page": "In God We Trust", "text_new": "{{short description|Official motto of the United States}}\n{{other uses|In God We Trust (disambiguation)}}\n\n[[File:1in god we trust.jpg|thumb|Capitalized \"{{sc|IN GOD WE TRUST}}\" on the reverse of a [[United States twenty-dollar bill]]]]\n\"'''In God We trust'''\", also written as \"'''In God we trust'''\"<!--Do Not Remove this form (In God we trust): Is found this way in the original statute and  this form has been discussed as an alternative form of the title of this article.-->, is the [[United States national motto|official motto]] of the [[United States|United States of America]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/BILLS-112hconres13rh/pdf/BILLS-112hconres13rh.pdf|title=H. CON. RES. 13|quote=Reaffirming \u2018\u2018In God We Trust\u2019\u2019 as the official motto of the United States|accessdate=13 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512223059/https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/BILLS-112hconres13rh/pdf/BILLS-112hconres13rh.pdf|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Title 36 \u2013 Patriotic and National Observances, Ceremonies, and Organizations|url=https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/USCODE-2017-title36/html/USCODE-2017-title36.htm|quote=\u00a7302. National motto \"In God we trust\" is the national motto.|accessdate=12 May 2019|website=U.S. Government Publishing Office|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512135913/https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/USCODE-2017-title36/html/USCODE-2017-title36.htm|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/36/302|website=LII / Legal Information Institute|title=36 U.S. Code \u00a7\u202f302. National motto|quote=\u201cIn God we trust\u201d is the national motto.|accessdate=12 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207221852/https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/36/302|archive-date=7 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Florida]]. It was adopted by the U.S. Congress in 1956, supplanting ''[[E pluribus unum]]'', in use since the initial 1776 design of the [[Great Seal of the United States]].<ref name=\"RSAL\">{{cite book |last1=Bittker |first1=Boris |last2=Idleman |first2=Scott |last3=Ravitch |first3=Frank |date=2015 |title=Religion and the State in American Law |publisher=Cambridge University Press |page=136 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=pduCCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA136&dq=%22e+pluribus+unum%22+1776+motto#v=onepage&q=%22e%20pluribus%20unum%22%201776%20motto&f=false|isbn=9781107071827 }}</ref>\n\nThe capitalized form \"IN GOD WE TRUST\" first appeared on the [[Two-cent piece (United States)|two-cent piece]] in 1864<ref name=\"USTreasury\">{{cite web|url=https://www.treasury.gov/about/education/Pages/in-god-we-trust.aspx|title=History of 'In God We Trust'|last=U.S. Department of the Treasury|date=2011|website=www.treasury.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2017-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417102334/https://www.treasury.gov/about/education/Pages/in-god-we-trust.aspx|archive-date=2016-04-17|url-status=live}}</ref> and has appeared on [[Federal Reserve Note|paper currency]] since 1957. A law passed in a Joint Resolution by the 84th Congress (P.L. 84\u2013140) and approved by President [[Dwight Eisenhower]] on July 30, 1956, requires that \"In God We Trust\" appear on American currency. The following year, the phrase was used on paper money for the first time\u2014on the updated one-dollar [[Silver certificate (United States)|silver certificate]] that entered circulation on October 1, 1957.<ref name=\"USTreasury\"/> The 84th Congress later passed legislation (P.L. 84\u2013851), also signed by President Eisenhower on July 30, 1956, declaring the phrase to be the national motto.<ref>{{USC|36|302}} ''National motto''</ref><ref name=\"USTFS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.treasury.gov/about/education/Pages/in-god-we-trust.aspx|title=U.S. on the History of \"In God We Trust\"|publisher=United States Department of the Treasury|accessdate=2009-04-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417182551/http://www.treasury.gov/about/education/Pages/in-god-we-trust.aspx|archive-date=2015-04-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"USPL84-851\">[http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/STATUTE-70/pdf/STATUTE-70-Pg732-2.pdf United States Public Law 84-851] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705011910/https://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/STATUTE-70/pdf/STATUTE-70-Pg732-2.pdf |date=2018-07-05 }}, United States Public Law 84-851.</ref>\n\nSome groups and people have objected to its use, contending that its religious reference violates the [[Establishment Clause]] of the [[First Amendment]].<ref>{{cite news |author=12 Mar 2010 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/7426824/Atheist-in-battle-to-remove-In-God-We-Trust-from-US-currency.html |title=Atheist in battle to remove 'In God We Trust' from US currency |newspaper=Telegraph |date=2010-03-12 |accessdate=2014-02-04 |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031114917/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/7426824/Atheist-in-battle-to-remove-In-God-We-Trust-from-US-currency.html |archive-date=31 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> These groups believe the phrase should be removed from currency and public property. In lawsuits, this argument has not overcome the interpretational doctrine of [[accommodationism]], which allows government to endorse religious establishments as long as they are all treated equally.<ref name=\"Drakeman1991\">{{cite book|last=Drakeman|first=Donald L.|title=Church-state Constitutional Issues: Making Sense of the Establishment Clause|date=1 January 1991|publisher=Greenwood Press|language=English |isbn=9780313276637}}</ref> According to a 2003 joint poll by [[USA Today]], [[CNN]], and [[The Gallup Organization|Gallup]], 90% of Americans support the inscription \"In God We Trust\" on U.S. coins.<ref name=Poll>{{cite news|title=USA TODAY/CNN/Gallup Poll results|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/polls/tables/live/2003-09-29-religion-poll.htm|quote=C. The inscription \"In God We Trust\" on U.S. coins; 2003 Sep 19\u201321; Approve 90; Disapprove 8; No opinion 2|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|year=2011|accessdate=15 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, \"In God We Trust\" was designated as the motto of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Florida]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.netstate.com/states/mottoes/fl_motto.htm|title=Florida State Motto In God We Trust|first=NSTATE, LLC|last=http://www.n-state.com|date=|website=www.netstate.com|access-date=2018-02-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170614202208/http://www.netstate.com/states/mottoes/fl_motto.htm|archive-date=2017-06-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"myflorida.com\">{{cite web|url=http://dos.myflorida.com/florida-facts/florida-state-symbols/state-motto/|title=State Motto \u2013 Florida Department of State|author=|date=|website=dos.myflorida.com|access-date=2018-02-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180216211708/http://dos.myflorida.com/florida-facts/florida-state-symbols/state-motto/|archive-date=2018-02-16|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThe [[Spanish language|Spanish]] equivalent of \"In God We Trust,\" ''En Dios Confiamos,'' is the motto of the [[Nicaragua|Republic of Nicaragua]].<ref>As shown on the [[Nicaraguan c\u00f3rdoba|C\u00f3rdoba]] (bank notes and coins); see for example [http://bcn.gob.ni/billetes_monedas/index.html?&val=1 Banco Central de Nicaragua]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506010635/http://www.bcn.gob.ni/billetes_monedas/index.html |date=2012-05-06 }}</ref> The [[heraldic motto]] of [[Brighton, England]] is the [[Latin]] equivalent, ''In Deo Fidemus''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alamy.com/the-coat-of-arms-of-brighton-with-motto-in-deo-fidemus-we-trust-in-god-on-wall-brighton-east-sussex-england-uk-in-april-image179873295.html|title=Stock Photo - The coat of arms of Brighton with Motto: 'IN DEO FIDEMUS' - We trust in God on wall, Brighton, East Sussex, England UK in April|first=Alamy|last=Limited|website=Alamy|access-date=2019-06-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190603073442/https://www.alamy.com/the-coat-of-arms-of-brighton-with-motto-in-deo-fidemus-we-trust-in-god-on-wall-brighton-east-sussex-england-uk-in-april-image179873295.html|archive-date=2019-06-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Chase to Pollock 1863-12-09 motto only.png|thumb|[[Salmon P. Chase|Salmon P. Chase, Treasury Secretary]], scribes \"In God is Our Trust,\" scratches out \"is Our\" and overwrites \"We\" to arrive at \"In God We Trust\" in a December 9, 1863, letter to [[James Pollock]], Director of the Philadelphia Mint.<ref>{{cite book|last=Chase|first=Salmon P|title=Letter to James Pollock|publisher=National Archives and Records Administration|work=Document # RG 104_UD 87-A_Folder In God We Trust 1861_Part1|page=11|date=December 9, 1863}}</ref>|left]]\n[[File:1864_2C_Small_Motto_Red_(obv).jpg|thumb|\"{{sc|IN GOD WE TRUST}}\" first appeared on the obverse side of the [[Two-cent piece (United States)|Two-cent piece]] in 1864<ref name=\"USTreasury\"/>|left]]\nIn 1860, the phrase was used in the [[coat of arms of New Westminster]], Canada. During the [[American Civil War]], the [[125th Pennsylvania Infantry]] for the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] [[Union Army|Army]] assumed the motto \"In God we trust\" in early August 1862.<ref>{{cite book|last=The Regimental Committee|first=125th PA Volunteers, 1862\u20131863|title=Regimental History|year=2009|publisher=Cornell University Library|location=Ithaca, NY|isbn=978-1-112-13570-5|pages=150\u2013152}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Alexander|first=ted|title=The Battle of Antietam|year=2011|publisher=The History Press|location=Charleston, SC|isbn=978-1-60949-179-6|page=76}}</ref><ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fLc6WDOMUwA|title=125th PA Vol. Infantry: IN GOD WE TRUST|date=28 June 2012|work=YouTube|access-date=29 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810041027/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fLc6WDOMUwA|archive-date=10 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> William W. Wallace, coiner, circa August 1862, of the motto \"In God We Trust\"{{sfn| Regimental Committee| 1906|p=151}} was Captain of Company C of the 125th Pennsylvania Infantry.\n\nThe Reverend [[Mark R. Watkinson]] of '[[Ridleyville]]', [[Pennsylvania]], (pastor of Prospect Hill Baptist Church in present-day [[Prospect Park, Pennsylvania]]) in a letter dated November 13, 1861, petitioned the Treasury Department to add a statement recognizing \"[[Almighty God]] in some form on our coins\" in order to \"relieve us from the ignominy of heathenism\".<ref name=Treasury>{{cite web|title=History of 'In God We Trust'|url=http://www.treasury.gov/about/education/Pages/in-god-we-trust.aspx|publisher=U.S. Department of the Treasury|accessdate=3 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417182551/http://www.treasury.gov/about/education/Pages/in-god-we-trust.aspx|archive-date=17 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"US-CSS\">United States (1897). ''Congressional Serial Set''. US: Government Printing Office, [https://books.google.com/books?id=Yv0qAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA260 p. 260.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118192336/https://books.google.com/books?id=Yv0qAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA260 |date=2016-11-18 }}</ref> At least part of the motivation was to declare that [[God]] was on the Union side of the [[American Civil War|Civil War.]]<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web|url=http://www.treasury.gov/about/education/Pages/in-god-we-trust.aspx|title=History of 'In God We Trust'|work=treasury.gov|accessdate=2016-04-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417182551/http://www.treasury.gov/about/education/Pages/in-god-we-trust.aspx|archive-date=2015-04-17|url-status=live}}</ref> Treasury Secretary [[Salmon P. Chase]] acted on this proposal and directed the then-Philadelphia [[Director of the United States Mint|Director of the Mint]], [[James Pollock]], to begin drawing up possible designs that would include the religious phrase. Chase chose his favorite designs and presented a proposal to Congress for the new designs in late 1863.<ref>Duncan, Ann W. (2008). [https://books.google.com/books?id=zzOn09EaETgC&pg=PA63 Religion, Rhetoric, and Ritual in the U.S. Government,\"] ''Church-state Issues in America Today''. Westport CT: Greenwood Publishing Group, [https://books.google.com/books?id=zzOn09EaETgC&pg=PA77 pp. 77.]</ref>\n\nIn December 1863, [[Abraham Lincoln]]'s Secretary of the Treasury decided on a new motto, \"In God We Trust,\" to engrave on U.S. coins. Lincoln's involvement in this decision is unclear.<ref>According to The ''Congressional Record'' (1908, House), p. 3387, the motto was adopted \"doubtless with his [Lincoln's] knowledge and approval\".\n</ref>\n\nA version of the motto made an early appearance on obverse side of the [[Interest bearing note#Denominational set of interest bearing notes|twenty dollar interest bearing note]] issued in 1864 along with the motto \"God and our Right\".\n\nAs Chase was preparing his recommendation to Congress, it was found that the Act of Congress dated January 18, 1837, prescribed the mottoes and devices that should be placed upon the coins of the United States. This meant that the mint could make no changes without the enactment of additional legislation by the Congress. Such legislation was introduced and passed as the [[Coinage Act of 1864]] on April 22, 1864, allowing the Secretary of the Treasury to authorize the inclusion of the phrase on one-cent and two-cent coins.<ref name=\"history\" />\n\nAn Act of Congress passed on March 3, 1865, allowed the Mint Director, with the Secretary's approval, to place the motto on all gold and silver coins that \"shall admit the inscription thereon\".<ref name=\"history\" /><ref name=CR1956p13917>[http://www.nonbeliever.org/images/CR102-13917.pdf ''Congressional Record'', 1956, p. 13917] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106115209/http://www.nonbeliever.org/images/CR102-13917.pdf |date=2009-01-06 }}, via NonBeliever.org</ref> In 1873, Congress passed the Coinage Act, granting that the Secretary of the Treasury \"may cause the motto IN GOD WE TRUST to be inscribed on such coins as shall admit of such motto\".\n\nA similar phrase, 'In God is our Trust', appears in \"[[The Star-Spangled Banner]]\", the song adopted as the national anthem of the United States in 1931. Written by [[Francis Scott Key]] during the [[War of 1812]], the fourth stanza includes the words, \"And this be our motto: 'In God is our Trust'\".<!--, which was adapted as the national motto.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://time.com/4179685/in-god-we-trust-currency-history/ |title=How 'In God We Trust' Got on the Currency in the First Place |first=Sarah |last=Begley |magazine=Time |date=January 13, 2016 |access-date=February 24, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180302112901/http://time.com/4179685/in-god-we-trust-currency-history/ |archive-date=March 2, 2018 |url-status=live |quote=Congress passed his act requesting the addition of \u201cIn God We Trust,\u201d adapted from a lesser-known verse of Francis Scott Key\u2019s \u201cStar-Spangled Banner,\u201d and the first two-cent coin with the phrase was minted in 1864.}}</ref>{{better source|reason=We have one 2016 article that mentions this supposed concious adaptation, but are there any other secondary sources that make this claim? For instance, are there any mentions of this connection from 1863, 1931 or 1956? Or maybe a later scholarly analysis of the motto?|date=March 2018}}-->\n[[File:1879S Morgan Dollar NGC MS67plus Reverse.png|thumb|The reverse of the [[Morgan dollar]] presented the lower-cased \"In God we trust\"]]\n[[File:2014 ATB Quarter Obv.png|thumb|right|A [[quarter dollar]] with the United States' official motto \"{{sc|IN GOD WE TRUST}}\" on the obverse side]]\nAfter use of the motto on coins began during the 1860s, there have been some coins on which the motto did not appear. The motto disappeared from the five-cent coin in 1883, and did not reappear until production of the Jefferson nickel began in 1938.<ref name=\"history\"/> However, at least two other coins minted in every year in the interim still bore the motto,{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} including the [[Morgan dollar]] and the [[United States Seated Liberty coinage|Seated Liberty half dollar]]. The omission of the motto \"In God We Trust\" on the [[Indian Head eagle]] coin caused public outrage, and prompted [[United States Congress|Congress]] to pass a bill mandating its inclusion.  Mint Chief Engraver [[Charles E. Barber]] added the words and made minor modifications to the design. In 1908, Congress made it mandatory that the phrase be printed on all coins upon which it had previously appeared. This decision was motivated after a public outcry following the release of a $20 coin which did not bear the motto.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.republicanpresidents.net/10-interesting-facts-about-theodore-roosevelt/ |title=10 Interesting Facts About Theodore Roosevelt |publisher=Republicanpresidents.net |date= 2009-03-04|accessdate=2014-02-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140217130709/http://www.republicanpresidents.net/10-interesting-facts-about-theodore-roosevelt/ |archive-date=2014-02-17 |url-status=live }}</ref> The motto has been in continuous use on the one-cent coin since 1909, and on the ten-cent coin since 1916. It also has appeared on all gold coins and silver dollar coins, half-dollar coins, and quarter-dollar coins struck since July 1, 1908.<ref name=\"history\"/> Since 1938, all US coins have borne the motto.<ref name=\"USTreasury\"/>\n\nDuring the [[Cold War]] era, the government of the United States sought to distinguish itself from the [[Soviet Union]], which promoted [[state atheism]] and thus implemented [[Soviet anti-religious legislation|antireligious legislation]].<ref>Merriman, Scott A. [https://books.google.com/books?id=l_8VFygyaDYC&pg=PA281&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false Religion and the Law in America: An Encyclopedia of Personal Belief and Public Policy] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529230649/https://books.google.com/books?id=l_8VFygyaDYC&pg=PA281&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=2019-05-29 }}. Santa Barbara, CA: ABC-CLIO, 2007. Print. \"In 1956, the United States, changed its motto to 'In God We Trust', in large part to differentiate itself from the Soviet Union, its Cold War enemy that was widely seen as promoting atheism.\"</ref> The [[84th United States Congress|84th Congress]] passed a joint resolution \"declaring IN GOD WE TRUST the national motto of the United States\". The resolution passed both the House and the Senate unanimously and without debate.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/249484657/?terms=in+god+we+trust|title=New National Motto Of U. S. Recalls Key's Words Of 1814|date=13 Aug 1956|page=8|work=[[Palladium-Item]]|location=Richmond, Indiana|via=Newspapers.com|access-date=2018-02-15|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226032430/https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/249484657/?terms=in+god+we+trust|archive-date=26 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>Miller, Douglas and Nowak, Marion'', The Fifties: The Way We Really Were''. 1977, 89. \"'In God We Trust' was adopted as the national motto in 1956, with neither debate nor a single dissenting vote in the House or Senate.\"</ref> H.R. 619, a bill that required that the inscription \"In God we trust\" appear on all paper and coin currency, was signed into law by President [[Dwight D. Eisenhower|Eisenhower]] on July 30, 1956.<ref>[[s:Public Law 84-851|Public Law 84-851]]</ref><ref name=\"History, Art & Archives\">{{cite web|url=https://history.house.gov/Historical-Highlights/1951-2000/The-legislation-placing-%E2%80%9CIn-God-We-Trust%E2%80%9D-on-national-currency/|title=The Legislation Placing \"In God We Trust\" on National Currency'|work=history.house.gov|accessdate=2019-09-16}}</ref> The United States Code at {{USC|36|302}}, now states: \"'In God we trust' is the national motto.\"\n\nOn paper currency, it first appeared on the [[Silver certificate (United States)|silver certificate]] in 1957, followed by other certificates.  [[Federal Reserve Note]]s and [[United States Note]]s were circulated with the motto starting from 1964 to 1966, depending on the denomination.<ref name=\"history\"/><ref>Steven B. Epstein, \"[https://www.jstor.org/stable/1123418 Rethinking the Constitutionality of Ceremonial Deism] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317235545/http://www.jstor.org/stable/1123418 |date=2017-03-17 }}\" Columbia Law Review, Vol. 96, No. 8. (Dec., 1996), p. 2083\u20132174, quoting the [[peroration]] (abridged here) of the speech by [[Charles Edward Bennett]], sponsor in the House, the only speech in either House of Congress on the subject. President Eisenhower and [[W. Randolph Burgess]], Deputy to the [[United States Secretary of the Treasury|Treasury for Monetary Affairs]], had approved of the legislation! 101 [[Congressional Record]] pp. 4384 (quoted), 7796. (1955)</ref> (Of these, only Federal Reserve Notes are still circulated.)\n\nRepresentative [[Charles Edward Bennett]] of Florida cited the Cold War when he introduced the bill in the House, saying \"In these days when imperialistic and materialistic communism seeks to attack and destroy freedom, we should continually look for ways to strengthen the foundations of our freedom\".\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://history.house.gov/Historical-Highlights/1951-2000/The-legislation-placing-%E2%80%9CIn-God-We-Trust%E2%80%9D-on-national-currency/ |title=The legislation placing \"In God We Trust\" on national currency &#124; US House of Representatives: History, Art & Archives |publisher=history.house.gov |date=1955-07-11 |accessdate=2017-05-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519004812/http://history.house.gov/Historical-Highlights/1951-2000/The-legislation-placing-%E2%80%9CIn-God-We-Trust%E2%80%9D-on-national-currency/ |archive-date=2017-05-19 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=dEADWZdN2k8C&pg=PA47 United States Currency Inscription]. Miscellaneous Hearings. Tuesday, May 17th 1955. House of Representatives. Committee on Banking and Currency. pps 47-57</ref>\n\n''[[Aronow v. United States]]'' was the first case to challenge the inclusion of \"In God We Trust\" on [[United States dollar|U.S. currency]].<ref name=\"AronowUS\">{{cite court |litigants=Aronow v. United States |vol=432 |no=23444 |reporter=F.2d |opinion=242 |pinpoint=243 |court=9th Cir. |date=October 6, 1970 |url=http://openjurist.org/432/f2d/242/aronow-v-united-states}}</ref> The law it challenged was \"31 U.S.C. \u00a7 324a \"the inscription 'In God we Trust'...shall appear on all United States currency and coins\".<ref name=\"AronowUS\"/> ''O'Hair v. Blumenthal'' (1978) challenged the inclusion of the phrase \"In God We Trust\" on U.S. currency. A similar decision was reached by the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit|Fifth Circuit]] in ''[[Madalyn Murray O'Hair]] vs [[W. Michael Blumenthal]]'' in 1979, which affirmed that the \"primary purpose of the slogan was secular\".<ref name=\"Duncan\">Duncan, Ann W. (2008). ''Church-state Issues in America Today''. Westport CT: Greenwood Publishing Group, [https://books.google.com/books?id=zzOn09EaETgC&pg=PA88 p. 88.]</ref>\n\nIn March 2001, [[Governor of Mississippi]] [[Ronnie Musgrove]] signed legislation requiring the motto \"In God We Trust\" to be displayed in every [[Public school (government funded)|public school]] classroom, as well as the school auditoriums and cafeterias, throughout the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pfaw.org/pfaw/general/default.aspx?oid=3643|title=Page not found|accessdate=20 December 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070807082223/http://www.pfaw.org/pfaw/general/default.aspx?oid=3643|archivedate=7 August 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/25/us/national-news-briefs-in-god-we-trust-motto-for-mississippi-schools.html|title=National News Briefs; 'In God We Trust' Motto For Mississippi Schools|first=The Associated|last=Press|date=25 March 2001|publisher=|accessdate=20 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222162529/http://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/25/us/national-news-briefs-in-god-we-trust-motto-for-mississippi-schools.html|archive-date=22 December 2017|url-status=live|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[September 11 attacks]] in 2001, many public schools across the United States posted \"In God We Trust\" framed posters in their \"libraries, cafeterias and classrooms\". The [[American Family Association]] supplied several 11-by-14-inch posters to school systems and vowed to defend any legal challenges to the displaying of the posters.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2002/02/20/usat-posters.htm|title=USATODAY.com \u2013 'In God We Trust' pressed for schools|work=usatoday.com|date=19 February 2002|access-date=23 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111072453/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2002/02/20/usat-posters.htm|archive-date=11 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 2003 joint poll by ''[[USA Today]]'', [[CNN]], and [[The Gallup Organization|Gallup]], 90% of Americans support the inscription \"In God We Trust\" on U.S. coins.<ref name=Poll/>\n\nIn 2006, on the 50th anniversary of its adoption, the [[United States Senate|Senate]] reaffirmed \"In God We Trust\" as the official national motto of the United States of America.<ref name=Senate>{{cite news|author=Felicia Sonmez|title=Social issues return to fore with 'In God We Trust' resolution|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/2chambers/post/social-issues-return-to-fore-with-in-god-we-trust-resolution/2011/10/31/gIQAXQasZM_blog.html|quote='In 2006, on the 50th anniversary of its adoption, the Senate reaffirmed 'In God We Trust' as the official national motto of the United States,' Forbes said in a statement announcing the vote. 'Tomorrow, the House of Representatives will have the same opportunity to reaffirm our national motto and directly confront a disturbing trend of inaccuracies and omissions, misunderstandings of church and state, rogue court challenges, and efforts to remove God from the public domain by unelected bureaucrats.'|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=7 November 2011|date=1 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104034201/http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/2chambers/post/social-issues-return-to-fore-with-in-god-we-trust-resolution/2011/10/31/gIQAXQasZM_blog.html|archive-date=4 November 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> In Florida House Bill no. 1145, Florida adopted 'In God We Trust' as the official state motto, effective July 1, 2006.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"myflorida.com\"/>\n\nIn 2011 the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] passed an additional resolution reaffirming \"In God We Trust\" as the official motto of the United States, in a 396\u20139 vote.<ref name=Reaffirm>{{cite news|author=Jennifer Steinhauer|title=In God We Trust, With the House's Help|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/02/us/house-of-representatives-affirms-in-god-we-trust-motto.html|quote=Citing a crisis of national identity and mass confusion among Americans about their nation's motto, the House on Tuesday voted on a resolution 'reaffirming \"In God We Trust\" as the official motto of the United States.'|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=7 November 2011|date=3 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111107012016/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/02/us/house-of-representatives-affirms-in-god-we-trust-motto.html|archive-date=7 November 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Iqraar>{{cite news|author=Todd Starnes|title=See Which Congressmen Voted Against 'In God We Trust'|url=http://nation.foxnews.com/congress/2011/11/01/see-which-congressmen-voted-against-god-we-trust#ixzz1cYiMXHil|quote=The House of Representatives passed a bi-partisan resolution Tuesday night reaffirming \"In God We Trust\" as the official motto of the United States. The 396\u20139 vote came at the request of Rep. Randy Forbes (R-VA).|publisher=[[Fox News]]|accessdate=7 November 2011|date=3 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104222412/http://nation.foxnews.com/congress/2011/11/01/see-which-congressmen-voted-against-god-we-trust#ixzz1cYiMXHil#ixzz1cYiMXHil|archive-date=2011-11-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, a federal court rejected a challenge, brought by [[Michael Newdow]] and the [[Freedom From Religion Foundation]], to remove \"In God We Trust\" from American currency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ksl.com/index.php?nid=1016&sid=26823999&fm=most_popular|title=Lawsuit to remove 'In God We Trust' from money gets dismissed - KSL.com|work=ksl.com|access-date=2018-02-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224232917/https://www.ksl.com/index.php?nid=1016&sid=26823999&fm=most_popular|archive-date=2018-02-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Seal_of_Mississippi_(2014-present).svg|thumb|\"{{sc|In God We Trust}}\" on the [[Seal of Mississippi]]|left]]\n\nOn January 31, 2014, purporting to defend religious freedom, the [[Mississippi]] senate voted to add the words, \"In God We Trust\" to the state seal and the change was made effective on July 1, 2014.<ref name=2014Seal>{{cite web|url=http://billstatus.ls.state.ms.us/documents/2014/pdf/SB/2600-2699/SB2681PS.pdf |title=Mississippi Religious Freedom Restoration Act; enact and modify the great seal. |work=Senate Bill No. 2681 |date=January 2014 |author=Mississippi Legislature |publisher=State of Mississippi |location=Mississippi |accessdate=April 2, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140402134106/http://billstatus.ls.state.ms.us/documents/2014/pdf/SB/2600-2699/SB2681PS.pdf |archivedate=April 2, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wagster Pettus |first=Emily |authorlink= |title=Miss. Senate OKs adding 'In God We Trust' to seal |publisher=WorldNow and WLBT |date=31 January 2014 |url=http://www.msnewsnow.com/story/24601213/miss-senate-oks-adding-in-god-we-trust-to-seal |doi= |accessdate=1 February 2014 }}{{dead link|date=August 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 the county police department of [[Jefferson County, Illinois]] announced that the words \"In God We Trust\" will be on police squad cars.<ref>\"[http://www.kfvs12.com/story/29683669/in-god-we-trust-to-be-placed-on-jefferson-co-il-squad-cars 'In God We Trust' to be placed on Jefferson Co., IL squad cars]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6aSm61nMB?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150801181841/http://www.kfvs12.com/story/29683669/in-god-we-trust-to-be-placed-on-jefferson-co-il-squad-cars Archive]). ''[[KFVS]]''. August 1, 2015. Retrieved on August 2, 2015.</ref> In 2015, the Freedom from Religion Foundation demanded that local authorities remove decals of the motto from Childress, Texas Police Department patrol vehicles. In response, Police Chief Adrian Garcia told the organization, in a written letter, to \"go fly a kite.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailysignal.com/2015/10/01/atheist-group-calls-for-removal-of-in-god-we-trust-police-car-decals-police-chief-says-go-fly-a-kite/|title=Atheist Group Asks Police Remove 'In God We Trust' Car Decal|author=|date=October 2015|website=dailysignal.com|access-date=2018-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225205846/http://dailysignal.com/2015/10/01/atheist-group-calls-for-removal-of-in-god-we-trust-police-car-decals-police-chief-says-go-fly-a-kite/|archive-date=2018-02-25|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Act 911, sponsored by State Rep. [[Jim Dotson]], made it a requirement of [[Arkansas]] state law for schools to display posters with the national motto (\"In God We Trust\").<ref>{{cite web|url=https://insider.foxnews.com/2018/03/12/god-we-trust-posters-be-displayed-arkansas-public-schools-after-donations|title='In God We Trust' Posters to Be Displayed in Arkansas Public Schools|date=12 March 2018|website=Fox News Insider|access-date=3 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190603120905/https://insider.foxnews.com/2018/03/12/god-we-trust-posters-be-displayed-arkansas-public-schools-after-donations|archive-date=3 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2018/mar/11/schools-will-display-in-god-we-trust-20/|title=Some Arkansas schools will display 'In God we trust' after posters donated|date=11 March 2018|website=Arkansas Online|access-date=3 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190603120850/https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2018/mar/11/schools-will-display-in-god-we-trust-20/|archive-date=3 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>  \n\nAlso in March, the same requirement was enacted <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/421883564/In-God-We-Trust-Law#from_embed|title=In God We Trust Law - KRS158.195-amended|website=scribd}}</ref> in Kentucky schools for the 2019-2020 school year requiring the slogan to be displayed \"in a prominent location.\" To protest the requirement, [[Fayette County Public Schools (Kentucky)]] in [[Lexington, KY]] complied by posting a framed [[United States one-dollar bill]] which bears the slogan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wkyt.com/content/news/In-God-We-Trust-found-in-form-of-dollar-bill-at-Fayette-County-school-542607641.html|title='In God We Trust' found in form of dollar bill at Fayette County schools|date=14 Aug 2019|website=WKYT|access-date=1 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901175508/https://www.wkyt.com/content/news/In-God-We-Trust-found-in-form-of-dollar-bill-at-Fayette-County-school-542607641.html|archive-date=1 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2018, [[Kimberly Daniels]], a [[pastor]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://charismanews.com/us/64103-apostle-kimberly-daniels-scores-big-win-for-prayer-in-public-schools|title=Apostle Kimberly Daniels Scores Big Win for Prayer in Public Schools|first=Charlene Aaron/CBN|last=News|date=|website=charismanews.com|access-date=2018-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225144903/https://charismanews.com/us/64103-apostle-kimberly-daniels-scores-big-win-for-prayer-in-public-schools|archive-date=2018-02-25|url-status=live}}</ref> who currently serves as the representative for [[Florida House of Representatives]] District 14 as a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], introduced HB 839, a bill that requires public schools to display the motto \"In God We Trust\" in a conspicuous place. On Tuesday, January 23, 2018, the bill received unanimous approval from the House PreK-12 Innovation Subcommittee.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/florida/fl-reg-in-god-we-trust-schools-20180124-story.html |title=Schools could be required to display 'In God we trust' |publisher=Sun Sentinel |date= |accessdate=2018-03-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306142624/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/florida/fl-reg-in-god-we-trust-schools-20180124-story.html |archive-date=2018-03-06 |url-status=live }}</ref> Later, in a vote on February 21, 2018, the bill passed 97 to 10 in the House.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/02/23/us/florida-in-god-we-trust-legislation-trnd/index.html|title=Florida lawmakers advance a bill that requires 'In God We Trust' displayed on school grounds|first=Joe |last=Sterling|date=|website=cnn.com|access-date=2018-02-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224113844/https://edition.cnn.com/2018/02/23/us/florida-in-god-we-trust-legislation-trnd/index.html|archive-date=2018-02-24|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/florida-lawmakers-give-go-ahead-bill-have-god-we-trust-school-buildings-818745|title=Florida lawmakers advance bill that would require 'In God We Trust' to be visible on all school buildings|author=|date=23 February 2018|website=newsweek.com|access-date=24 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224165636/http://www.newsweek.com/florida-lawmakers-give-go-ahead-bill-have-god-we-trust-school-buildings-818745|archive-date=24 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> As part of Florida's March 2018 K-12 education law, Gov. [[Rick Scott]] mandated that all public schools post the state motto (\"In God We Trust\") in a prominent location.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tampabay.com/blogs/gradebook/2018/03/26/atheist-group-offers-to-provide-in-god-we-trust-signs-to-florida-public-schools/|title=Atheist group offers to provide \"In God We Trust\" signs to Florida public schools|date=26 March 2018|website=Tampa Bay Times|access-date=3 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190603120850/https://www.tampabay.com/blogs/gradebook/2018/03/26/atheist-group-offers-to-provide-in-god-we-trust-signs-to-florida-public-schools/|archive-date=3 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, a bill requiring Tennessee schools to prominently display the national motto (\"In God We Trust\") sponsored by Rep. [[Susan Lynn]] passed the state House with 81 of the 99 members voting in favor of it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/religion/2018/03/21/tennessee-lawmakers-pass-bill-requiring-public-schools-post-god-we-trust-motto/442884002/|title=Tennessee lawmakers pass bill requiring public schools to post 'In God We Trust' motto|website=The Tennessean}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, the [[Bakersfield, California]] City Council voted 4-2 to put an \"In God We Trust\" sticker on the city's police and fire vehicles. The issue was debated for two hours by 19 people including a lawyer from the [[ACLU]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sam |first1=Morgan |title='In God We Trust' decals to be placed on local police, fire vehicles |url=https://www.bakersfield.com/news/in-god-we-trust-decals-to-be-placed-on-local/article_fb214930-880a-11e9-9042-03579af67a08.html |accessdate=6 June 2019 |publisher=bakersfield.com/TBC Media |date=6 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607003302/https://www.bakersfield.com/news/in-god-we-trust-decals-to-be-placed-on-local/article_fb214930-880a-11e9-9042-03579af67a08.html |archive-date=7 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2019, South Dakota <ref name=\"abc1\">https://abcnews.go.com/US/south-dakota-public-schools-now-required-display-god/story?id=64587406</ref> and Louisina <ref name=\"abc1\" /> passed bills that requires public schools to display the motto \"In God We Trust\".\n\nOn March 3, 2020, the [[Oklahoma House of Representatives]] passed a bill that would require public buildings in the state to display In God We Trust.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://oklahoman.com/article/5656492/oklahoma-house-approves-in-god-we-trust-bill|title=Oklahoma House approves 'In God We Trust' bill|website=[[The Oklahoman]]|date=4 March 2020|accessdate=5 March 2020|author=Carmen Forman}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2020 Kansas, Indiana, and Oklahoma are looking at similar bills.<ref>https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/kansas-considers-requiring-god-trust-classrooms-68646918</ref><ref>https://www.wlwt.com/article/top-10-novel-coronavirus-questions-answered-by-a-doctor/31897112</ref><ref>https://apnews.com/db16988fa3140b9fef588d9ca8d1358d</ref>\n\n==Society and culture==\n===Religion===\nIn [[Judaism]] and [[Christianity]], the official motto \"In God We Trust\" is not found verbatim in any verses from the [[Bible]], but very closely in the Old Testament in {{Bibleverse||Psalm|91:2|KJV}}, \"I will say of the LORD, ''He is'' my refuge and my fortress: my God; in him will I trust\" and in the New Testament in {{Bibleverse||2 Corinthians|1:10|KJV}}, \"Who delivered us from so great a death, and doth deliver: in whom we trust that he will yet deliver ''us''.\"  The concept is paraphrased in {{Bibleverse||Psalm|118:8|KJV}}, {{Bibleverse||Psalm|40:3|KJV}}, {{Bibleverse||Psalm|73:28|KJV}}, and {{Bibleverse||Proverbs|29:25|KJV}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=In God We Trust: The Motto|url=http://www.allabouthistory.org/in-god-we-trust.htm|publisher=All About History|accessdate=2013-02-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130216035526/http://www.allabouthistory.org/in-god-we-trust.htm|archive-date=2013-02-16|url-status=live}}</ref> In [[Islam]] the word for the concept of reliance on God is called ''[[Tawakkul]]''; the phrase \"In God We Trust\" is literally found in two places of the [[Quran]], in [[Surah]] 10 [[Yunus (surah)|Yunus]], as well as [[Surah]]  [[Al-A'raf]](7:89), and several other verses reinforce this concept.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://quranindex.net/kelime.php?id=8603 |title=Verses including the word Putting One's Trust in Allah (Tawakkul) |publisher=Quran Index |accessdate=2016-06-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007144200/http://quranindex.net/kelime.php?id=8603 |archive-date=2016-10-07 |url-status=live }}</ref> Melkote Ramaswamy, a Hindu American scholar, writes that the presence of the phrase \"In God We Trust\" on American currency is a reminder that \"there is God everywhere, whether we are conscious or not.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Ramaswamy |first=Melkote |url=http://www.indystar.com/article/20120811/LIFE04/208110323/In-Hinduism-there-just-one-God-many-forms |title=Faith/Values &#124; Indianapolis Star |publisher=indystar.com |date=2012-08-11 |accessdate=2014-02-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141019115759/http://www.indystar.com/article/20120811/LIFE04/208110323/In-Hinduism-there-just-one-God-many-forms |archive-date=2014-10-19 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===In popular culture===\nAn e-mail conspiracy theory is that \"In God We Trust\" was intentionally omitted from new U.S. dollar coins in 2007.<ref>\"Historic Change\", Snopes, http://www.snopes.com/politics/religion/dollarcoin.asp</ref>  The first coins produced under the [[Presidential $1 Coin Program]] did indeed lack the \"In God We Trust\" inscription along their edges (along with the \"E Pluribus Unum\" inscription, the year of production, and the [[mint mark]]; these coins, unlike normal dollar coins, had completely blank edges), but these coins, known as \"[[Presidential $1 Coin Program#Minting errors|godless dollars]]\", were the result of a minting error, not a deliberate omission.<ref>{{cite web |author=David S Morgan |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/03/07/national/main2543125.shtml?source=RSSattr=HOME_2543125 |title=\"Godless\" Dollar Coins Slip Through Mint |publisher=CBS News |date=2007-03-07 |accessdate=2010-11-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424224759/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/03/07/national/main2543125.shtml?source=RSSattr=HOME_2543125 |archive-date=2011-04-24 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[http://biz.yahoo.com/ap/070307/godless_dollars.html?.v=3 Associated Press: Dollar Coins Missing 'In God We Trust'], By David S Morgan, (Mar. 7, 2007), CBS News {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070319223227/http://biz.yahoo.com/ap/070307/godless_dollars.html?.v=3 |date=March 19, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe film ''[[They Live]]'' (1988) plays on the idea. Special sunglasses allow the wearers to see simple hidden messages instead of the signs they see without them. Advertising is seen as \"OBEY\", \"CONSUME\" and \"MARRY AND REPRODUCE\". Dollar bills are all marked \"THIS IS YOUR GOD\".<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Rothkopf |first=Joshua |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/features/how-they-live-took-on-the-republicans-and-won-20141027 |title=\"Empire of the Sunglasses: How 'They Live' Took on Republicans and Won\", by Joshua Rothkopf, ''Rolling Stone'' |magazine=Rollingstone.com |date=2014-10-27 |accessdate=2018-03-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615111808/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/features/how-they-live-took-on-the-republicans-and-won-20141027 |archive-date=2018-06-15 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2006, [[Laurence Llewelyn-Bowen]] and his wife Jackie were offered a place on the [[Valentine's Day]] celebrity couples edition of ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (UK game show)|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]'' They appeared on the show managing to reach the \u00a31 million question, before answering it incorrectly and dropping from \u00a3500,000 all the way down to just \u00a332,000 (a loss of \u00a3468,000). Celador allowed Llewelyn-Bowen and his wife retry the show after the company claimed that the last question \"didn't meet their standards\". The allegedly misleading question was \"Translated from the [[Latin language|Latin]], what is the motto of the United States?\" The answer given was \"In God We Trust\" which is originally English and has in fact been the motto of the United States since 1956. The intended answer had been \"One Out of Many\" which is a translation of the Latin phrase ''[[E pluribus unum]]'', which is not actually the current United States motto. ''E pluribus unum'' had been the de facto motto but was never legally declared as such.<ref name=\"secondchance\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4608690.stm|title=TV designer's second shot at \u00a31m|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|date=13 January 2006|accessdate=22 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725015341/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4608690.stm|archive-date=25 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===License plates===\n[[File:2008 South Carolina license plate In God We Trust 000 000.png|thumb|\"In God We Trust\" optional [[South Carolina license plates|license plate]] designed by Troy Wingard for the [[South Carolina Department of Public Safety]] in 2002]]\nAs of April 1, 2016 the following U.S. states currently offer an \"In God We Trust\" license plate as a specialty plate for an additional normal vehicle registration processing which vary from state to state: Alaska, Arizona, Arkansas, Florida, Indiana, Kansas, Kentucky, Louisiana, North Carolina, Ohio,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://codes.ohio.gov/orc/4503.763|title=4503.763 Ohio Battleflag license plates.|website=Ohio Administrative Code|publisher=Lawriter LLC|quote=\"Ohio Battleflag\" license plates shall be inscribed with the words \"In God We Trust\"|access-date=2018-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180530035758/http://codes.ohio.gov/orc/4503.763|archive-date=2018-05-30|url-status=live}}</ref> Oklahoma, Pennsylvania, South Carolina, Tennessee, Texas, Utah, Virginia, West Virginia, and Wisconsin.{{citation needed |date=April 2018}}\n\nFlorida \u2014 which also offers a specialty plate \u2014 and Georgia which both display the county of issuance on their License Plate offer the option of \"In God We Trust\" in place of the County Name.{{citation needed |date=April 2018}}\n\n==Criticism==\nThe constitutionality of the phrase \"In God We Trust\" has been upheld according to the judicial interpretation of [[accommodationism]], whose adherents state that this entrenched practice has not historically presented any constitutional difficulty, is not coercive, and does not prefer one religious denomination over another.<ref name=\"Views\" />  In ''[[Zorach v. Clauson]]'' (1952), the Supreme Court also wrote that the nation's \"institutions presuppose a Supreme Being\" and that government recognition of [[God]] does not constitute the establishment of a state church as the Constitution's authors intended to prohibit.<ref name=ABA>{{cite book|title=ABA Journal Sep 1962|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gymQ6vWfA3QC&pg=PA817&dq=Zorach+v.+Clauson+++In+God+We+Trust#v=onepage&q=Zorach%20v.%20Clauson%20%20%20In%20God%20We%20Trust&f=false|quote=Much more recently, in 1952, speaking through Mr. Justice Douglas in ''Zorach v. Clauson'', 343 U.S. 306, 313, the Supreme Court repeated the same sentiments, saying: We are a religious people whose institutions presuppose a Supreme Being. Mr. Justice Brewer in the ''Holy Trinity'' case, ''supra'', mentioned many of these evidences of religion, and Mr. Justice Douglas in the ''Zorach'' case referred to&nbsp;... [P]rayers in our legislative halls; the appeals to the Almighty in the messages of the Chief Executive; the proclamation making Thanksgiving Day a holiday; \"So help me God\" in our courtroom oaths \u2013 these and&nbsp;... other references to the Almighty&nbsp;... run through our laws, our public rituals, our ceremonies&nbsp;... the supplication with which the Court opens each session: \"God save the United States and this Honorable Court\" (312\u2013313). To this list may be added tax exemption of churches, chaplaincies in the armed forces, the \"Pray for Peace\" postmark, the widespread observance of Christmas holidays, and, in classrooms, singing the fourth stanza of ''America'' which is prayer invoking the protection of God, and the words \"in God is our trust\" as found in the National Anthem, and the reciting of the Pledge of Allegiance to the Flag, modified by an Act of Congress of June 14, 1954, to include the words \"under God.|access-date=September 24, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161119065015/https://books.google.com/books?id=gymQ6vWfA3QC&pg=PA817&dq=Zorach+v.+Clauson+++In+God+We+Trust#v=onepage&q=Zorach%20v.%20Clauson%20%20%20In%20God%20We%20Trust&f=false|archive-date=November 19, 2016|url-status=live|date = September 1962}}</ref> \n\nOn the other hand, advocates of [[Separation of church and state in the United States|separation of church and state]] have questioned the legality of this motto asserting their opinion that it is a violation of the United States Constitution, prohibiting the government from passing any law respecting an establishment of religion.<ref name=Views>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vonnZcMHs8kC&pg=PA60|title=The Dynamic Constitution: an Introduction to Americans Constitutional Law|author=Richard H. Fallon|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|page=60|quote=\"Strict separationists\" believe that the government has no business supporting religious beliefs or institutions in any way \u2013 for example, by providing tax breaks to churches, assisting parochial schools, including prayers or benedictions in public ceremonies, or inscribing \"In God We Trust\" on the currency. Religious accommodationists can well explain why certain entrenched social practices (such as the inscription of \"In God We Trust\" on the currency) were not historically perceived as presenting constitutional difficulties: The relevant practices are not coercive and do not prefer one narrow sect over another.|isbn=978-0-521-60078-1|year=2004|access-date=2016-09-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118232121/https://books.google.com/books?id=vonnZcMHs8kC&pg=PA60|archive-date=2016-11-18|url-status=live}}</ref> As such \"In God We Trust\" as a national motto and on U.S. currency has been the subject of numerous unsuccessful lawsuits by these individuals.<ref name=\"AtheistLawsuit\">{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/05/29/atheist-lawsuit-currency-god_n_5412890.html |title=Atheists Lose Latest Battle To Remove 'In God We Trust' From U.S. Currency |last1=Markoe |first1=Lauren |date=2014-05-29 |website=huffingtonpost.com |publisher=[[Religion News Service]] |accessdate=2014-10-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018001553/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/05/29/atheist-lawsuit-currency-god_n_5412890.html |archive-date=2014-10-18 |url-status=live }}</ref> The motto was first challenged in ''[[Aronow v. United States]]'' in 1970, but the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]] ruled: \"It is quite obvious that the national motto and the slogan on coinage and currency 'In God We Trust' has nothing whatsoever to do with the establishment of religion. Its use is of patriotic or ceremonial character and bears no true resemblance to a governmental sponsorship of a religious exercise.\"<ref>Aronow, 432 F.2d at 243.</ref> In ''[[Lynch v. Donnelly]]'' (1984), the Supreme Court wrote that acts of \"[[ceremonial deism]]\" are \"protected from Establishment Clause scrutiny chiefly because they have lost through rote repetition any significant religious content\".<ref>[http://caselaw.lp.findlaw.com/scripts/getcase.pl?court=US&vol=465&invol=668 LYNCH v. DONNELLY, 465 U.S. 668 (1984)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101216213127/http://caselaw.lp.findlaw.com/scripts/getcase.pl?court=us&vol=465&invol=668 |date=2010-12-16 }} U.S. Supreme Court</ref>\n\nIn June 2006, a federal judge rejected [[Michael Newdow]]'s Establishment Clause lawsuit on the grounds that the minted words amount to a secular national slogan, and do not dictate anyone's beliefs. Newdow stated that he would appeal the ruling,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,199211,00.html | title=Federal Judge Nixes 'In God We Trust' Lawsuit | publisher=[[Fox News Channel]] | date=2006-06-12 | access-date=2018-02-24 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021151309/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,199211,00.html | archive-date=2012-10-21 | url-status=dead }}</ref> although ''Aronow'' was decided on the same grounds in the Ninth Circuit and the lower court was required to return the same ruling, likewise the Ninth Circuit does not traditionally overrule previous Ninth Circuit rulings. On December 4, 2007, Newdow argued before a three-judge panel of the Ninth Circuit to remove both \"under God\" from the Pledge of Allegiance (''Roe v. Rio Linda Union School District''),{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}} and \"In God We Trust\" from United States currency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fl1.findlaw.com/news.findlaw.com/hdocs/docs/religion/newdowus91405opn.pdf|title=Newdow v. Congress of the United States|website=findlaw.com|access-date=2018-02-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052152/http://fl1.findlaw.com/news.findlaw.com/hdocs/docs/religion/newdowus91405opn.pdf|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Ninth Circuit rejected Newdow's challenge. In a decision published March 11, 2010, the court held that its earlier decision in ''Aronow'', which \"held the national motto is of a \"patriotic or ceremonial character,\" has no \"theological or ritualistic impact,\" and does not constitute \"governmental sponsorship of a religious exercise,\" foreclosed Newdow's argument.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2010/03/11/06-16344.pdf | title=Newdow v. Lefevre, No. 06-16344, at 4210 (9th Cir. Mar. 11, 2010) (citing ''Aronow'', 432 F.2d at 243\u201344). | access-date=2018-02-24 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916170940/http://www.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2010/03/11/06-16344.pdf | archive-date=2012-09-16 | url-status=live }}</ref> In an opinion concurring only in the judgment, even the Judge [[Stephen Reinhardt]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.theweeklystandard.com/Content/Public/Articles/000/000/001/414ilyss.asp | title=Matt Rees, ''The Judge the Supreme Court Loves to Overturn'', '''The Weekly Standard''', May 5, 1997; | access-date=2018-02-24 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100516024714/http://www.theweeklystandard.com/Content/Public/Articles/000/000/001/414ilyss.asp | archive-date=2010-05-16 | url-status=dead }} compare {{cite news | url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-03-03/news/mn-42564_1_supreme-court | title=David G. Savage, ''Crusading Liberal Judge Keeps High Court Busy'', '''L.A. Times''', Mar. 3, 1996. | work=The Los Angeles Times | date=1996-03-03 | access-date=2018-02-24 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022232558/http://articles.latimes.com/1996-03-03/news/mn-42564_1_supreme-court | archive-date=2012-10-22 | url-status=live }}</ref> agreed that ''Aronow'' was controlling precedent.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2010/03/11/06-16344.pdf | title=''Newdow'', at 4210\u201311 (Reinhardt, J., concurring). | access-date=2018-02-24 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916170940/http://www.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2010/03/11/06-16344.pdf | archive-date=2012-09-16 | url-status=live }}</ref> ''Newdow v. Congress'', 598 F.3d 638 (9th Cir. 2010) cert. denied 131 S. Ct. 1612 (U.S. 2011). AKA: The \"In God We Trust Case\" \u2013 A prominent atheist, Michael Newdow, filed a suit to declare the national motto \u2013 In God We Trust \u2013 unconstitutional and to have it removed from coins and currency.<ref name=\"egelko\">Bob Egelko, 'In God We Trust' suit rejected by Supreme Court, ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', [http://www.sfgate.com/nation/article/In-God-We-Trust-suit-rejected-by-Supreme-Court-2471527.php] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180213222045/https://www.sfgate.com/nation/article/In-God-We-Trust-suit-rejected-by-Supreme-Court-2471527.php |date=2018-02-13 }} March 8, 2011</ref><ref name=\"ninth-circuit\">[[Ninth Circuit]] [[Court of Appeals]], ''Newdow v. Congress'', [http://www.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2010/03/11/06-16344.pdf] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916170940/http://www.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2010/03/11/06-16344.pdf |date=2012-09-16 }} March 11, 2010</ref><ref name=\"oral-arguments\">[[C-SPAN]] Video Library, ''Establishment of Religion Clause Oral Arguments, Part 1'', [http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/ClauseO&showFullAbstract=1] December 7, 2007</ref> [[Pacific Justice Institute]] intervened as a defendant and defended against the suit.<ref name=\"egelko\"/><ref name=\"ninth-circuit\"/><ref name=\"oral-arguments\"/>  The case was dismissed by the trial court and the Ninth Circuit affirmed that decision.<ref name=\"egelko\"/><ref name=\"ninth-circuit\"/><ref name=\"oral-arguments\"/>\n\nIn 2015, [[David F. Bauman]] dismissed a case against the [[Matawan-Aberdeen Regional School District]] brought by a student of the district and the [[American Humanist Association]] that argued that the phrase \"under God\" in the [[Pledge of Allegiance (United States)|Pledge of Allegiance]] created a climate of discrimination because it promoted religion, making non-believers \"second-class citizens\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northjersey.com/news/hearing-under-god-in-pledge-of-allegiance-does-not-violate-rights-of-atheist-students-nj-judge-rules-1.1332137|title=Hearing 'Under God' in Pledge of Allegiance does not violate rights of atheist students, NJ judge rules|author=Salvador Rizzo|work=NorthJersey.com|access-date=February 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310061721/http://www.northjersey.com/news/hearing-under-god-in-pledge-of-allegiance-does-not-violate-rights-of-atheist-students-nj-judge-rules-1.1332137|archive-date=March 10, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/maureensullivan/2015/02/07/judge-refuses-to-kick-god-out-of-public-schools/#11e06914435f|title=Judge Refuses To Kick God Out Of Public Schools|date=February 7, 2015|work=Forbes|access-date=February 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160229082828/http://www.forbes.com/sites/maureensullivan/2015/02/07/judge-refuses-to-kick-god-out-of-public-schools/#11e06914435f|archive-date=February 29, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> He noted; \"As a matter of historical tradition, the words 'under God' can no more be expunged from the national consciousness than the words 'In God We Trust' from every coin in the land, than the words 'so help me God' from every presidential oath since 1789, or than the prayer that has opened every congressional session of legislative business since 1787.\"\n\nPresident [[Theodore Roosevelt]] took issue with using the motto on coinage considering its usage \"dangerously close to [[sacrilege]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1907/11/14/archives/roosevelt-dropped-in-god-we-trust-president-says-such-a-motto-on.html|title=Roosevelt Dropped 'IN GOD WE TRUST'; President Says Such a Motto on Coin Is Irreverence, Close to Sacrilege. NO LAW COMMANDS ITS USE He Trusts Congress Will Not Direct Him to Replace the Exalted Phrase That Invited Constant Levity|date=November 14, 1907|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=26 August 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226032944/https://www.nytimes.com/1907/11/14/archives/roosevelt-dropped-in-god-we-trust-president-says-such-a-motto-on.html|archive-date=26 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>{{quotation|\"... My own feeling in the matter is due to my very firm conviction that to put such a motto on coins, or to use it in any kindred manner, not only does no good, but does positive harm, and is in effect irreverence, which comes dangerously close to sacrilege. ...&nbsp; Any use which tends to cheapen it, and, above all, any use which tends to secure its being treated in a spirit of levity, is from every standpoint profoundly to be regretted. ... it seems to me eminently unwise to cheapen such a motto by use on coins ...&nbsp; In all my life I have never heard any human being speak reverently of this motto on the coins or show any signs of its having appealed to any high emotion in him, but I have literally, hundreds of times, heard it used as an occasion of and incitement to ... sneering ...&nbsp; Every one must remember the innumerable cartoons and articles based on phrases like 'In God we trust for the 8 cents,' ...&nbsp; Surely, I am well within bounds when I say that a use of the phrase which invites constant levity of this type is most undesirable. ...\" - Theodore Roosevelt, November 1907}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"160\">\nFile:Obama_Health_Care_Speech_to_Joint_Session_of_Congress.jpg|\"IN GOD WE TRUST\" motto over 